"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541088","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-05","<p>The UK is and continues to be a shareholder of the European Investment Bank and the EIB has publically stated that its engagement in the UK is unchanged.</p><p>All existing loan contracts signed between UK promoters and the EIB remain in force, and the EIB has continued to sign and approve new projects since the referendum.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-09-05T13:12:02.5Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541088/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541088/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541088/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-20","Transport: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on (a) signed European Investment Bank (EIB) loans for transport projects in the UK and (b) EIB loan applications that are under appraisal for transport projects in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","43562"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541089","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Department is undertaking work to understand the environmental impacts of additional airport capacity. Further details on procurement undertaken to support the Department on environmental impacts can be found here: <a href="https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/17ffaddc-3c19-4462-91ae-bf30029c08d9" target="_blank">https://www.contractsfinder.service.gov.uk/Notice/17ffaddc-3c19-4462-91ae-bf30029c08d9</a>.</p><p> </p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-08T14:00:26.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541089/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541089/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541089/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-20","London Airports: Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the environmental assurance work his Department undertook in December 2015 in connection with runway expansion has been completed; and what the estimated cost of that work was to the public purse on the latest date for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","43553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541090","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-07","<p>Rail passengers should always be able to get the best deal and the industry must work harder to make this a reality. Train operators have made some improvements and passengers are benefiting from better on-screen information at some stations but there has got to be improvement right across the network. I have raised this with the Rail Delivery Group that represents all train operating companies as there is clearly more to be done.</p><p> </p><p>The Office of Rail and Road (ORR) have plans to undertake customer focused research and analysis of ticket vending machines with findings and next steps to be published in Spring 2017. This follows their recent Annual Rail Consumer Report (June 2016), which identified issues with existing ticket vending machines. We support this work by the ORR in its role as consumer regulator and will continue to challenge the industry to address the issues and make improvements as soon as possible.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-09-07T13:28:30.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541090/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541090/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541090/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-20","Railways: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent assessment he has made of the effectiveness of automated ticket machines in ensuring that rail commuters are always offered the lowest fare.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","43483"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541091","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-07","<p>There is a dedicated, ring-fenced, fund for Network Rail’s work to improve and close level crossings. As is usual, the Department’s work on the policy underpinning the level crossing reform programme forms part of a larger budget for railway safety and wider issues and is not therefore separately identifiable.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-09-07T13:43:52.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541091/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541091/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541091/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-20","Level Crossings: Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 27 June 2016 to Question 40827, what his Department's revenue expenditure other than Network Rail expenditure was on the level crossing reform programme in the last Parliament; and how much such expenditure is budgeted for during the current Parliament.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","43498"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541093","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-05","<p>Department for Transport officials continue to work with their European and international counterparts on both matters.</p><p> </p><p>Ships operating in an emission control area (ECA) – such as the North Sea (including the English Channel) and Baltic Sea – are already subject to a 0.1 per cent sulphur limit. The next sulphur limit to affect shipping will be the 0.5 per cent global cap for ships when operating outside an ECA. The limit will apply in 2020, subject to the outcome of IMO’s review of fuel availability, which could see its application deferred until 2025. The review’s findings will be considered at the next session of the IMO’s Marine Environment Protection Committee (MEPC), which takes place in October 2016.</p><p> </p><p>Regarding measures to reduce carbon emissions from ships, we expect a global data collection system on fuel consumption from ships to be adopted at the upcoming MEPC meeting. This is the first step in a process considering further technical and operational measures to enhance the energy efficiency of shipping. Officials will also play an active role in the Working Group at the same meeting to discuss how international shipping can play its part in delivering the goals of the Paris Agreement on climate change.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-05T13:31:41.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541093/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541093/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541093/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-20","Shipping: Exhaust Emissions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with his European counterparts on promoting (a) a sulphur limit and (b) decarbonisation measures through the International Maritime Organisation.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","43521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541094","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-07","<p>We want smart tickets to be available to passengers across the entire rail network providing them with more convenience and choice. By the end of the year the South East Flexible Ticketing programme will have introduced smart ticketing on five of the major London and south east rail operators. In the North of England, we have committed £150m to support Transport for the North (TfN) in its plans to introduce smart ticketing.</p><p> </p><p>The Rail Delivery Group have brought the rail industry together to agree a long-term vision and it is critical that rail operators collaborate and share ideas to make this vision a reality. Through franchising competitions we are supporting the rail industry to develop and deliver modernised ticketing by setting challenging requirements for bidders, ensuring that customers benefit from a 21st century option. Many rail travellers are familiar with using the orange magnetic stripe ticket and I will ensure that this is not withdrawn until alternatives are in place that offer a user experience with which all travellers are comfortable, particularly vulnerable customer groups.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-09-07T13:35:33.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541094/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541094/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541094/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-20","Railways: Tickets","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress has been made in implementing smart ticketing across the rail network; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","43491"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541095","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-09","<p>The title of this group is the South East Quadrant.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-09-09T08:45:15.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541095/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541095/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541095/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-20","Railways: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 17 June 2016 to Question 40286, asked by the hon. Member for Greenwich and Woolwich, what the title is of the group that meets monthly.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","43657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541096","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-07","<p>The Local Enterprise Partnerships are planning to contribute £13 million from Local Growth Deals as part of this government’s record investment in the rail network.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-09-07T13:15:04.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541096/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541096/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541096/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-20","Railways: Market Harborough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, pursuant to the Answer of 9 May 2016 to Question 36626, what contributions he expects the Local Enterprise Partnerships to make towards the cost of the Market Harborough straightening works.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","43656"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541097","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-05","<p>The table below provides the number of cyclists killed in a road traffic accident on public roads in a) Redcar, b) the North East of England, and c) Great Britain.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Redcar constituency</p></td><td><p>North East England</p></td><td><p>Great Britain</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>111</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>107</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>118</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>6</p></td><td><p>109</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>3</p></td><td><p>113</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>100</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Department does not hold data for Northern Ireland, therefore the table includes statistics for Great Britain rather than the United Kingdom.</p><p> </p><p>These statistics come from police reported data on personal injury accidents on the public highway. The Department does not collect information about accidents that were on private roads, car parks or off-road.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-05T12:55:27.957Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541097/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541097/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541097/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-20","Cycling: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many cyclists died as a result of road traffic incident in each year since 2010 in (a) Redcar, (b) the North East and (c) the UK.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","43614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541098","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-07","<p>Network Rail is now evaluating electrification of routes on a case by case basis as one of the ways of delivering enhanced train services to meet the forecast growth in rail usage.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2016-09-07T13:20:57.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541098/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541098/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541098/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-20","Railways: Electrification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he expects Network Rail to publish an update to its industry electrification strategy.","false","Biography information for Greg Mulholland","Leeds North West","Greg Mulholland","43597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541099","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-05","<p>Following the previous Chancellor’s further statement in July 2015 that the Government is looking at extending Mersey Gateway bridge toll discounts to residents of Chester West &amp; Chester and Warrington, officials are currently working through what the proposed further extension means for the scheme both by way of the cost to the Department but also and importantly what this would do to the commercial structure of the contracts already signed for the scheme. Once this is clear we will be able to provide more information.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","43610","2016-09-05T14:03:16.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541099/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541099/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541099/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-20","River Mersey: Bridges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what recent discussions he has had with the Chancellor of the Exchequer about the introduction of tolls on the Mersey Gateway and Silver Jubilee bridges; and whether a decision has been taken on discounts for local businesses and residents.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","43608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541100","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-05","<p>The Department does not hold any information on the number of lanes in either the road accident data supplied by police forces or road traffic estimates. Therefore it is not possible to provide a comparison between dual carriageway roads and single carriage roads with three lanes.</p><p> </p><p>However, the Department does record the number of carriageways at the scene of accidents as well as the length of ‘A’ roads by number of carriageways. As a guide, in 2015 for Great Britain there were 380 reported personal-injury accidents per billion vehicle miles on single carriageway ‘A’ roads and 140 accidents per billion vehicle miles on dual carriageway ‘A’ roads.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-09-05T11:59:49.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541100/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541100/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541100/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-20","Roads: Accidents","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether the average accident rate is higher on dual carriageways than on three lane roads.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire","43722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541101","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-05","<p>Although a two lane dual carriageway might be expected to cost more to build than a three lane single carriageway, simply because it is wider, the costs involved in building new carriageways are influenced by a wide range of considerations specific to the particular location, such as topography, cost of acquiring land etc.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-05T15:20:42.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541101/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541101/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541101/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-20","Roads: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether dual carriageways are more expensive to build than three lane roads.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire","43723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541102","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-05","<p>The Government is committed to upgrading all single carriageway sections of the A303 and A358 between the M3 and M5 to dual carriageway standard. In respect of the A303/A30 between Southfields and Honiton, Highways England will assess the options for improvements, including dualling, as part of its South West Peninsula route strategy, for which evidence gathering is underway. All interested parties are encouraged to submit evidence on the performance of this route through the tool at: <a href="http://www.highways.gov.uk/route-strategies/" target="_blank">www.highways.gov.uk/route-strategies</a>.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-05T15:23:54.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541102/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541102/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541102/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-20","Roads: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will re-evaluate the dualling of the entire A303/A30 corridor.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire","43724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541103","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-05","<p>The Road Investment Strategy, covering the period 2015 to 2020, commits funding for small-scale improvements to the A303/A30 between Southfields and Honiton to improve safety and journey quality, alongside a £2bn commitment to upgrade the A303 as a strategic corridor to the South-West. The Department and Highways England are gathering evidence to inform plans for investment in the Strategic Road Network post-2020, and decisions about further investment in this route will be made as part of this process.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-05T15:27:09.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541103/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541103/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541103/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-20","Roads: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether his Department will (a) approve and (b) fund the upgrade of the A303/A30 between Southfields and Honiton.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire","43725"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541104","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-05","<p>Following the previous Chancellor’s further statement in July 2015 that the Government is looking at extending Mersey Gateway bridge toll discounts to residents of Chester West &amp; Chester and Warrington, officials are currently working through what the proposed further extension means for the scheme both by way of the cost to the Department but also and importantly what this would do to the commercial structure of the contracts already signed for the scheme. Once this is clear we will be able to provide more information.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","43608","2016-09-05T14:03:16.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541104/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541104/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541104/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-20","River Mersey: Bridges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what criteria he will use to determine eligibility for discounted travel as part of the local discount scheme when tolls on the Mersey Gateway and Silver Jubilee bridges are introduced.","false","Biography information for Maria Eagle","Garston and Halewood","Maria Eagle","43610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541105","Wales Office","false","2016-09-05","<p>The Wales Office has no direct employees or contracted workers. Staff at the Wales Office are subject to Ministry of Justice (MoJ) policies for pay and agency contract purposes. No permanent staff working at the Wales Office are paid less than the living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation. We have less than five agency staff and none are paid less than the national living wage. No staff are on zero hours contracts.</p>","Aberconwy","Guto Bebb",,"2016-09-05T10:56:10.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541105/answer","Biography information for Guto Bebb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541105/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541105/answer",,,,,,,,,"28","Wales","Wales","2016-07-20","Wales Office: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Wales, how many people working for his Department on a (a) directly employed, (b) agency or (c) outsourced basis are paid less than the living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation; and how many of those people are employed on zero-hours contracts.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","43513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541107","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-06","<p>The Government introduced the National Living Wage on 1 April 2016. This will put over £900 more a year in the pockets of full-time workers compared to the current National Minimum Wage.</p><p> </p><p>The Department ensures that all direct employees are paid at least the mandatory National Living Wage set by the Government, regardless of age. Similarly all agency staff and those on outsourced contracts are paid at least this rate. The Department reviews pay annually, setting pay at rates that will attract and motivate appropriate numbers and sufficient talent to fulfil its duties to some 22 million customers.</p><p> </p><p>None of our employees nor those working for our contractors are on zero hours contracts.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-09-06T12:32:45.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541107/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541107/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541107/answer","Romsey and Southampton North","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541107/answer/previousversion/9330","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541107/answer/previousversion/9330","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-20","Department for Work and Pensions: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people working for his Department or its executive agencies on a (a) directly employed, (b) agency or (c) outsourced basis are paid less than the living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation; and how many of those people are employed on zero-hours contracts.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","43515"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541108","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-05","<p>Statistical information on Attendance Allowance claimants, including the numbers of cases in payment in each parliamentary constituency, is available from the DWP Tabulation Tool: <a href="http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/100pc/tabtool.html" target="_blank">http://tabulation-tool.dwp.gov.uk/100pc/tabtool.html</a></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-09-05T10:59:30.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541108/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541108/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541108/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-20","Attendance Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in each parliamentary constituency receive attendance allowance.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","43519"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541109","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-05","<p>None.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2016-09-05T10:55:17.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541109/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541109/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541109/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-20","Local Government: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government on the introduction of the cost collection process within the Local Government Pension Scheme.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","43486"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541110","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-05","<p>The specific information requested could only be obtained at a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Unlike tax credits which meant that claimants received demands for repayments and could never be sure they were receiving the correct entitlement, Universal Credit assesses monthly earnings and income in that month. That lessens the burden on claimants who have fluctuating incomes or irregular payments so they can budget with greater confidence and without the anxiety they will be hit with a demand for repayment.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently implementing a test and learn approach to understand the interaction of Universal Credit and employer pay cycles and its effect on awards. This work will include discussions with employers.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","43550 ; 43746 ; 43747","2016-09-05T11:19:35.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541110/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541110/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541110/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-20","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what his estimate is of the number of people in receipt of universal credit in regular employment and paid monthly whose pay date will fluctuate with their universal credit assessment period resulting in two sets of earnings in one assessment period and no earnings in the following assessment period since the roll-out of the digital service.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","43551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541111","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-05","<p>The specific information requested could only be obtained at a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Unlike tax credits which meant that claimants received demands for repayments and could never be sure they were receiving the correct entitlement, Universal Credit assesses monthly earnings and income in that month. That lessens the burden on claimants who have fluctuating incomes or irregular payments so they can budget with greater confidence and without the anxiety they will be hit with a demand for repayment.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently implementing a test and learn approach to understand the interaction of Universal Credit and employer pay cycles and its effect on awards. This work will include discussions with employers.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","43551 ; 43746 ; 43747","2016-09-05T11:19:35.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541111/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541111/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541111/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-20","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the average loss incurred by people in receipt of universal credit in regular employment and paid monthly whose pay date fluctuates with their universal credit assessment period resulting in two sets of earnings in one assessment period and no earnings in the following assessment period, compared with claimants whose pay date does not fluctuate with their assessment period resulting in one set of earnings in each assessment period since the roll-out of the digital service.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","43550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541112","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-05","<p>The specific information requested could only be obtained at a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Universal Credit is assessed and paid in a way that fits with the vast majority of claimants in work who are paid monthly. For a minority of cases, there will be instances where UC payments do not align with an individual’s wages, such as those who are paid 4-weekly.</p><p> </p><p>We have consulted and liaised with employers about Universal Credit and its interaction with labour market and employers processes and recommend, where they can, employers align with Universal Credit.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently implementing a test and learn approach to understand the interaction of Universal Credit and employer pay cycles and its effect on awards. This work will include discussions with employers.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-09-05T13:10:48.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541112/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541112/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541112/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-20","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many employees in receipt of universal credit are paid (a) monthly on the same date each month, (b) monthly on the same day of the week in each month, (c) 4-weekly, (d) 2-weekly and (e) weekly.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","43533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541113","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-05","<p>Throughout the life of Universal Credit, officials and Ministers have consulted and liaised with employers about Universal Credit and its interaction with labour market and employers’ processes.</p><p> </p><p>We are currently implementing a test and learn approach to understand the interaction of Universal Credit and employer pay cycles and its effect on awards. This work will include discussions with employers.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-09-05T13:06:44.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541113/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541113/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541113/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-20","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many employers have been advised that their pay cycles might affect universal credit payments; how many employers have altered their pay cycles as a result of that advice; and how many employees have been affected by such alterations.","false","Biography information for Debbie Abrahams","Oldham East and Saddleworth","Debbie Abrahams","43532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541114","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-05","<p>The latest available data on personal independence payment (PIP) registrations and clearances split by geographical area (local authority and parliamentary constituency) and by type of clearance (i.e. whether the claim was awarded, disallowed or withdrawn) for both new claims and reassessed claims, can be found at <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>. Guidance on how to use Stat-Xplore can be found here: <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The latest available data on personal independence payment (PIP) mandatory reconsideration registrations and clearances by type (e.g. 'New decision - Award changed') for Great Britain, for both new claims and reassessed claims, can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-april-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-april-2016</a> (Tables 7a and 7b). These statistics will include a number of mandatory reconsiderations that have been raised against awarded claims as well as disallowed (rejected) claims.</p><p> </p><p>To answer your questions in full, and provide a further breakdown of the mandatory reconsideration data for the Edinburgh North and Leith constituency, can only be done at a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of PIP appeals and their outcomes is published by the Ministry of Justice (MoJ). A link to the latest national level statistics published on 6 June 2016 can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics#employment-tribunal-and-employment-appeal-tribunal-statistics-gb" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics#employment-tribunal-and-employment-appeal-tribunal-statistics-gb</a></p><p>See table 2.7. However, the data is not published at lower geographical levels. Further enquiries should be referred to MoJ.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","43590","2016-09-05T13:26:05.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541114/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541114/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541114/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-20","Personal Independence Payment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many applications for personal independence payments have been rejected since the introduction of that benefit; and how many of those rejected applications have been overturned by (a) mandatory reconsideration and (b) tribunal hearing.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","43589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541115","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-05","<p>The latest available data on personal independence payment (PIP) registrations and clearances split by geographical area (local authority and parliamentary constituency) and by type of clearance (i.e. whether the claim was awarded, disallowed or withdrawn) for both new claims and reassessed claims, can be found at <a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/</a>. Guidance on how to use Stat-Xplore can be found here: <a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/index.html</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The latest available data on personal independence payment (PIP) mandatory reconsideration registrations and clearances by type (e.g. 'New decision - Award changed') for Great Britain, for both new claims and reassessed claims, can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-april-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/personal-independence-payment-april-2013-to-april-2016</a> (Tables 7a and 7b). These statistics will include a number of mandatory reconsiderations that have been raised against awarded claims as well as disallowed (rejected) claims.</p><p> </p><p>To answer your questions in full, and provide a further breakdown of the mandatory reconsideration data for the Edinburgh North and Leith constituency, can only be done at a disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of PIP appeals and their outcomes is published by the Ministry of Justice (MoJ). A link to the latest national level statistics published on 6 June 2016 can be found here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics#employment-tribunal-and-employment-appeal-tribunal-statistics-gb" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/tribunals-statistics#employment-tribunal-and-employment-appeal-tribunal-statistics-gb</a></p><p>See table 2.7. However, the data is not published at lower geographical levels. Further enquiries should be referred to MoJ.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt","43589","2016-09-05T13:26:05.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541115/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541115/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541115/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-20","Personal Independence Payment: Edinburgh North and Leith","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many applications for personal independence payments have been rejected since the introduction of that benefit in Edinburgh North and Leith constituency; and how many of those rejected applications have been overturned by (a) mandatory reconsideration and (b) tribunal hearing.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","43590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541116","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-05","<p>HMRC provide a tailored support service for vulnerable customers. If a customer who is terminally ill advises HMRC that they require extra help, HMRC's 'Needs Enhanced Support' team will help the customer throughout the claims procedure, accelerating the process where appropriate.</p><p> </p><p>There are no current plans for HMRC to introduce a specific fast track service for tax credit customers who are terminally ill<strong>. </strong></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-09-05T13:02:10.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541116/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541116/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541116/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-20","Welfare Tax Credits: Terminal Illnesses","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to process tax credits claims for terminally ill people; and if he will consider introducing a fast track system as applied to claims for other allowances.","false","Biography information for Tommy Sheppard","Edinburgh East","Tommy Sheppard","43603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541117","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-08","<p>The table below shows the details of actual and forecast expenditure for the staff cost of the Department’s Strategic Communications Directorate.</p><p> </p><p>The staff costs include the costs of salaries, employer national insurance contribution, employer pension contribution, performance related awards, overtime, travelling time, temporary duty allowance, secondments, contractors and staff substitutions. Also, associated IT costs and communications directorate external contracts are included.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial Year</p></td><td><p>Staff Costs £m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>17.543</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014/15</p></td><td><p>15.277</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015/16</p></td><td><p>15.109</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016/17*</p></td><td><p>15.134</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><em>*forecast as at July 2016</em></p><p> </p><p>Following a significant organisational design review (ODR) which resulted in fundamental structural changes within the Corporate Centre of DWP, expenditure prior to 2013/14 is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-09-08T11:35:55.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541117/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541117/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541117/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-20","Department for Work and Pensions: Communication","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the cost to his Department was of its communications team in each year since 2007; and what the projected cost is of that team in 2016.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","43591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541118","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-05","<p>Trustees and managers are responsible for acting in the best interests of beneficiaries, including the investment of members’ funds. They must, under existing obligations, prepare a statement of investment principles. This must set out the extent to which social, environmental, or ethical considerations are taken into account in the selection, retention, and realisation of investments.</p><p> </p><p>We have no immediate plans to change these existing obligations, but will keep them under review.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","43594","2016-09-05T11:40:30.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541118/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541118/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541118/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-20","Pension Funds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will review the powers of UK pensions schemes to indirectly invest in companies linked with the manufacture of cluster-munitions.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","43619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541119","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-09-05","<p>Trustees and managers are responsible for acting in the best interests of beneficiaries, including the investment of members’ funds. They must, under existing obligations, prepare a statement of investment principles. This must set out the extent to which social, environmental, or ethical considerations are taken into account in the selection, retention, and realisation of investments.</p><p> </p><p>We have no immediate plans to change these existing obligations, but will keep them under review.</p>","Watford","Richard Harrington","43619","2016-09-05T11:40:30.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541119/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541119/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541119/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-20","Pension Funds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether his Department plans to bring forward legislative proposals to ban the indirect investment by pension schemes in companies linked with the manufacture of cluster munitions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","43594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541120","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-09-05","<p>Investment decisions in the local government pension scheme are the responsibility of the 90 designated administering authorities in England and Wales and must be taken on the basis of expert advice and in compliance with the Scheme’s regulatory framework. Since 2000, pension fund authorities have been required to publish a statement of investment principles, including their policy on the extent to which social, environmental or ethical considerations are to be taken into account in the selection, retention and realisation of investments. The regulations also require that each statement is published locally.</p><p>We have no immediate plans to change these existing obligations, but will keep them under review.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","43618","2016-09-05T16:13:30.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541120/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541120/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541120/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-20","Local Government: Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will publish guidance for local authority pension schemes on investment in arms companies producing banned munitions; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","43617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541121","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-05","<p>The UK’s commitment to tackling global climate change is firm. Until we leave the EU, the UK will remain a full member, with all of the rights and obligations this entails.</p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-09-05T12:55:17.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541121/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541121/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541121/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Climate Change: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether it remains his Department's policy to meet EU climate targets; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","43620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541122","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-05","<p>The Government remains committed to meeting its commitments under its existing domestic climate framework, the Climate Change Act (CCA). Climate change remains one of the most serious long-term risks to our economic and national security.</p><p> </p><p>Under the CCA, the Government has now set the fifth carbon budget (2028-2032) at an equivalent 57% reduction on a 1990 baseline. This is in line with the recommendations of our independent Committee on Climate Change. The referendum does not affect this domestic decision, or our commitment to meet our emission targets cost effectively.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-09-05T12:55:50.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541122/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541122/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541122/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether his Department plans to set new climate targets as a result of the outcome of the EU referendum; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","43621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541123","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-05","<p>This Government is committed to regional development and supporting growth up and down the country as we build an economy that works for everyone. We are focused on developing an industrial strategy that will boost productivity, create good jobs, and ensure sustainable economic growth. The employment rate in the UK is now at a record high of 74.5% and the unemployment rate is at its lowest level in over 10 years at 4.9%.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to put power in the hands of local communities to drive economic growth. For Liverpool City Region, this includes implementing the devolution deal agreed with the Government in November 2015, which includes commitments around skills funding and co-designing future employment support for harder-to-help claimants. We will also work with Liverpool to deliver the city region’s Growth Deal which encompasses key projects across the city region and, for St Helens, includes improvements to Newton-le-Willows station and upgrades to the A570 to support growth in employment sites in the area.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-09-05T16:05:35.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541123/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541123/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541123/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to protect employment levels in (a) St Helens North constituency, (b) Merseyside and (c) the UK.","false","Biography information for Conor McGinn","St Helens North","Conor McGinn","43622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541124","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-05","<p>The Government considers safety and security at nuclear power plants to be of paramount importance. The operator bears most of the security costs for nuclear power plants. The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy seeks independent costs estimates for new nuclear power, which incorporate security costs – the Department’s most recent cost estimates are available in the Electricity Generation Costs report, available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/269888/131217_Electricity_Generation_costs_report_December_2013_Final.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/269888/131217_Electricity_Generation_costs_report_December_2013_Final.pdf</a></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-09-05T12:51:46.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541124/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541124/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541124/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Nuclear Power","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the implications for his Department's costings for nuclear power of the findings of the National Audit Office in its report published in July 2016 on Nuclear power in the UK, HC 511, paragraph 2.11, on the effect on running costs of nuclear power facilities of increased terrorist threats.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","43602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541125","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-13","<p>A number of former BIS policy areas are shifting to the Department for Education. Around 450-500 people and posts, working in these areas will be shifting to the Department for Education. Approximately 90 of these are in the regions.</p><p> </p><p>Given the machinery of government change we will be considering in the coming months how the reform plans of BEIS’ two predecessor departments should best be aligned.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-09-13T15:28:05.657Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541125/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541125/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541125/answer","Orpington","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541125/answer/previousversion/9323","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541125/answer/previousversion/9323","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans he has to review the BIS 2020 programme in the light of the restructuring of government departments.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","43629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541126","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-13","<p>Given the machinery of Government change we will be considering in the coming months how the reform plans of BEIS’ two predecessor departments should best be aligned.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-09-13T15:26:08.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541126/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541126/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541126/answer","Orpington","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541126/answer/previousversion/9324","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541126/answer/previousversion/9324","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Location","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will reverse the former Department of Business, Innovation and Skills plans to centralise that Department's policy functions in London.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","43630"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541127","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-11-14","<p>As of 1 November 2016, there are 21 members of staff based in the Sheffield office at St Paul’s Place. Following the recent Machinery of Government changes, BEIS is considering how to best align the reform agendas of its predecessor departments.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-11-14T14:23:01.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541127/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541127/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541127/answer","Orpington","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541127/answer/previousversion/9326","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541127/answer/previousversion/9326","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many of his Department's staff are based in the Sheffield office at St Paul's Place; and what plans he has for the future of those jobs.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","43631"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541128","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","true","2016-10-19","<p><del class="ministerial">The Department announced its decision earlier this year to create a combined headquarters and policy function in London, to deliver a simpler, smaller department that is more flexible and responsive to stakeholders and businesses by 2020. This involves basing all policy roles in London by 2018, which will include those roles working on Industrial Strategy issues. </del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">Given the recent Machinery of Government changes, over the coming months BEIS will be considering what the right structure for the Department should be, in order to deliver its objectives.</ins></p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-10-19T16:20:28.813Z","2017-01-16T16:20:09.92Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541128/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541128/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541128/answer","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner ; Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner ; Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd ; Mr Nick Hurd","Mr Nick Hurd ; Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541128/answer/previousversion/15315 ; http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541128/answer/previousversion/9321","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd ; Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541128/answer/previousversion/15315 ; http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541128/answer/previousversion/9321","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd ; Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans he has to base staff of his Department working on industrial strategy in offices outside London.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","43632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541129","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-05","<p>The UK was represented by Peter Betts, Director, International Climate Change at what was formerly DECC, now BEIS, and another government official.</p><p> </p><p>The full conclusions of the meeting are published by the German government at:</p><p><a href="http://www.bmub.bund.de/fileadmin/Daten_BMU/Download_PDF/Klimaschutz/petersberg7_conclusions_bf.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.bmub.bund.de/fileadmin/Daten_BMU/Download_PDF/Klimaschutz/petersberg7_conclusions_bf.pdf</a> and included as an annex here to be published in the House Libraries.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-09-05T12:53:04.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541129/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541129/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541129/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Climate Change: Conferences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, which (a) minister and (b) Government officials attended the Petersberg Climate Dialogue on 4 and 5 July 2016; and what the outcomes of that meeting were.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","43574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541130","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-05","<p>The UK remains firmly committed to the Paris Agreement and to ratifying the Agreement as soon as possible. Until we leave the EU, the UK will remain a full member, with all of the rights and obligations this entails.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-09-05T12:52:13.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541130/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541130/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541130/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Climate Change Convention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the UK plans to ratify the Paris Agreement on climate change separately and independently of the EU.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","43575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541131","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-13","<p>I am the Minister for Small Business, Consumers and Corporate Responsibility and I lead on competition law. I have a particular focus on ensuring that companies including directors, shareholders and employees achieve high standards of corporate behaviour to ensure that the public has trust in business and recognises their value to society.</p><p>I have specific responsibility for the UK’s register of People with Significant Control. I lead on the Department’s interests in transposing the Fourth Anti Money Laundering Directive. I am also the lead Minister for the Department on taking forward the UK’s commitments agreed at the May anticorruption summit in London.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-09-13T16:02:07.233Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541131/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541131/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541131/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Corruption","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, which Minister in his Department has responsibility for tacking corruption.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","43582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541132","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-05","<p>No immediate changes are needed to the UK’s legislation on climate change in order to implement our obligations under the Paris Agreement. The UK is already playing its part in delivering the Agreement through its Climate Change Act 2008. The Committee on Climate Change has said that it will report in the Autumn on the future implications of Paris for the UK. We shall want to consider carefully the CCC’s recommendations.</p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-09-05T14:08:44.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541132/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541132/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541132/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Climate Change Convention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of whether it will be necessary to bring forward new (a) primary or (b) secondary legislation to implement the UK's obligations under the Paris Agreement on climate change.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","43578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541133","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-05","<p>The UK remains firmly committed to the Paris Agreement and to ratifying the Agreement as soon as possible. Until we leave, the UK will remain a full member of the EU, with all of the rights and obligations this entails.</p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-09-05T12:53:35.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541133/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541133/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541133/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Climate Change Convention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the ratification of the Paris Agreement on climate change in the UK will follow the procedure for an EU external treaty.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","43576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541134","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-10-12","<p>The UK’s commitment to the Paris Agreement and to climate action is firm. An explanatory memorandum initiating the UK’s domestic approval of the Agreement was laid on 7<sup>th</sup> October 2016 with a view to completing domestic procedures before the end of the year.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-10-12T16:06:29.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541134/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541134/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541134/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Climate Change Convention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he plans to lay an explanatory memorandum before Parliament on the ratification of the Paris Agreement on climate change.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","43577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541135","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-13","<p>The Government remains committed to ensuring that the UK has one of the most competitive and productive life sciences sectors in the world, which is at the forefront of 21<sup>st</sup> century healthcare and technology. That is crucial to ensuring both improved health outcomes for patients and wider prosperity and economic growth.</p><p>The Government has created a supportive life sciences environment, including through significant support for research and development, both through the Research Councils and the National Institute for Health Research; support for innovation via Innovate UK; and support for exporters from the Department for International Trade. In 2014 UK Government spend on health research and development stood at just over £2.2bn<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup>.</p><p>The Government’s investment in life sciences benefits many areas of the UK. For example, Government has invested £20m in a joint fund between Greater Manchester and Cheshire &amp; Warrington Local Economic Partnerships, through Growth Deals.</p><p> </p><p>[1] ONS UK Government Expenditure on Science, Engineering and Technology, <a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/economy/governmentpublicsectorandtaxes/researchanddevelopmentexpenditure/datasets/scienceengineeringandtechnologystatisticsreferencetables" target="_blank">http://www.ons.gov.uk/economy/governmentpublicsectorandtaxes/researchanddevelopmentexpenditure/datasets/scienceengineeringandtechnologystatisticsreferencetables</a></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-09-13T15:10:54.98Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541135/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541135/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541135/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Life Sciences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to support and develop the UK life sciences industry; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","43556"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541136","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-13","<p>As at 1 August 2016 (following the implementation of the 2016 pay award) there are no direct employees in the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (former Department for Business, Innovation and Skills or former Department for Energy and Climate Change) paid less than the living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation.</p><p>As at this date there are no agency staff in former DECC paid less than the living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation.</p><p>There are 5 agency staff in former BIS paid less than the Living Wage Foundation’s definition. However, all 5 are paid more than the Government’s Living Wage rate of £7.20 per hour.</p><p>We do not centrally hold details of the pay levels of staff working for outsourced companies contracted by former BIS. Arm Length Bodies linked to former DECC have confirmed that they pay all their employees above the level set by the Living Wage Foundation.</p><p>There are no employees on zero hours contracts.</p><p>I have asked Chief Executives of the executive agencies of former BIS to respond directly to the Hon. Member.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-09-13T15:13:51.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541136/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541136/answer","agencies response PQ 43499.pdf","ex-BIS agencies response","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541136/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Living Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many people working for his Department or its executive agencies on a (a) directly employed, (b) agency or (c) outsourced basis are paid less than the living wage as defined by the Living Wage Foundation; and how many of those people are employed on zero-hours contracts.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","43499"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541137","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-05","<p>Responsibility for formulating and overseeing regulation of the shale gas industry has been transferred to the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy. The Department will fulfil the same role previously undertaken by the Department of Energy and Climate Energy.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has been clear that shale development must be safe and environmentally sound. The Royal Society and Royal Academy of Engineering concluded that risks can be managed if industry follows best practice enforced by regulation <strong>[1]</strong>. We already have one of the most robust regulatory regimes in the world for shale gas and we will look to continuously improve it as the industry develops.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><em><strong>[1]</strong></em><em> The Royal Society and The Royal Academy of Engineers, Shale gas extraction in the UK: a review of hydraulic fracturing, 2012</em></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-09-05T12:54:09.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541137/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541137/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541137/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Fracking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what responsibilities his Department has for (a) formulating and (b) overseeing regulation of the shale gas industry; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","43477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541138","Department for International Trade","false","2016-09-09","<p>The EU is currently negotiating a trade deal with Mercosur. Until we have left the EU, the UK will remain a member of the EU with all of the rights and obligations that membership entails.</p><p>In due course, Britain will be leaving the EU. This offers us an opportunity to forge a new role for ourselves in the world: to negotiate, in time, our own trade agreements and to be a positive and powerful force for free trade. The Prime Minister has established the Department for International Trade to promote British trade across the world and ensure the UK takes advantage of the huge opportunities open to us. The Government is currently reviewing its trade policy. We will engage fully with a broad range of stakeholders, including both governments and business over the coming weeks and months as we prepare for the negotiation with the EU and other international partners.</p><p> </p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-09-09T13:52:28.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541138/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541138/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541138/answer",,,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-20","Trade Agreements: Mercosur","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps his Department is taking to negotiate a trade deal with the Mercosur trading bloc.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","43476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541139","Department for International Trade","false","2016-09-09","<p>I refer the hon.Member to the answer given by my rt hon. Friend the Minister for the Cabinet Office, Ben Gummer, on 6 September 2016, UIN: <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-09-02/44131/" target="_blank">44131</a>.</p>","North Somerset","Dr Liam Fox",,"2016-09-09T12:01:48.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541139/answer","Biography information for Dr Liam Fox","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541139/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541139/answer",,,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-20","Department for International Trade: Ministers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, which Minister in his Department has responsibility for tackling corruption.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","43581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541140","Department for International Trade","false","2016-09-09","<p>The Department is continuously seeking to identify and share best practice from across the UK.</p><p>The Department works in partnership with Swindon &amp; Wiltshire Local Enterprise Partnership (LEP) and Swindon Borough Council to deliver foreign direct investment to Swindon. My officials will continue to work with them to look at further examples of best practice.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-09-09T12:10:02.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541140/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541140/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541140/answer",,,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-20","Foreign Investment in UK","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, if his Department will look at examples of best practice in attracting foreign direct investment (a) in Swindon and (b) across the UK.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","43670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541141","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-05","<p>The Government takes air pollution seriously and is committed to improving the UK’s air quality, reducing health impacts, and fulfilling our legal obligations.</p><p> </p><p>Directive 2008/1/EC, the Integrated Pollution, Prevention and Control Directive (IPPCD) has been superseded by the Industrial Emissions Directive (IED, 2010/75/EU) which brought together seven related directives including the IPPCD and the Large Combustion Plant Directive.</p><p> </p><p>Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force. During this period the Government will continue to negotiate, implement and apply EU legislation. The outcome of these negotiations will determine what arrangements apply in relation to EU legislation and funding in future once the UK has left the EU.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2016-09-05T10:20:36.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541141/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541141/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541141/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-20","Pollution Control","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what her policy is on future collaboration with the EU on tackling pollution and Directive 2008/1/EC.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541142","Home Office","false","2016-09-05","<p>Until Article 50 negotiations have concluded, the UK remains a full member of the EU, with all the rights and obligations that brings, and UK authorities continue to cooperate with their counterparts in other EU Member States, including on the European Arrest Warrant (EAW). The Government is exploring options for cooperation arrangements once the UK has left the EU. However, it would be wrong to set out unilateral positions in advance of negotiations.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","43741","2016-09-05T16:34:48.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541142/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541142/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541142/answer","Great Yarmouth","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis","Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541142/answer/previousversion/9180","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541142/answer/previousversion/9180","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-20","Police: Cross Border Cooperation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make it her policy to continue British access to the Schengen Information System for law enforcement purposes once the UK exits the EU.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43744"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541143","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-05","<p>The Department has been billed for £12,711 in relation to legal fees since it was established. Detailed work is underway to establish the Department's future budget requirements, including for legal advice.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-09-05T15:55:29.093Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541143/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541143/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541143/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-20","Department for Exiting the European Union: Legal Opinion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how much his Department has spent to date on legal advice; and how much he estimates will be so spent during 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541144","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-05","<p>We are preparing for negotiations to exit the EU. As part of these preparations, we will consider future trading relationships with both the EU and internationally. Tariffs on agricultural commodities, such as the level of sugar tariffs, will be one element of this work.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-09-05T14:56:09.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541144/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541144/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541144/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-20","Cane Sugar: Import Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what plans she has to review the tariffs imposed on cane sugar imports in the course of negotiations on exiting the EU; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","43734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541145","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-07","<p>There are a number of factors that the Government will need to consider when developing our strategy for negotiating our withdrawal from the European Union. The Department is working closely with businesses to understand their concerns and I will be working with colleagues across government to make sure we understand all of the potential risks and opportunities across the economy. This will continue to inform our approach as we seek to shape our future relationship with Europe.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-09-07T10:27:43.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541145/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541145/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541145/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Manufacturing Industries: EU Internal Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the potential cost to (a) the aerospace industry, (b) the car manufacturing industry and (c) other manufacturing in the UK of not having access to the EU Single Market.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541146","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-13","<p>The European Organization for Nuclear Research (CERN) and the European Space Agency (ESA) are separate organisations from the European Union and thus the UK’s memberships of CERN or ESA are not dependent on its EU membership. The UK will continue to play a leading role in major non-EU research collaborations, including CERN and ESA. In July we confirmed the UK’s application to become a full member of a major new particle accelerator, the European Spallation Source in Sweden.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","43708","2016-09-13T15:11:48.427Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541146/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541146/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541146/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","CERN","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what his policy is on future British involvement in the European Organization for Nuclear Research and the CERN research facility.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541148","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-05","<p>The government is keenly aware of the importance of these sectors to the economy. The new department is undertaking a great deal of factual and detailed work to establish how best to deliver the government's objectives, to ensure that we achieve the best possible outcome for the British people.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-09-05T15:46:00.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541148/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541148/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541148/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-20","Service Industries: EU Internal Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the potential costs to the (a) financial sector, (b) legal services sector and (c) professional services sector of not having access to the EU Single Market.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43673"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541149","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-05","<p>The Department has been billed for £12,711 in relation to legal fees since it was established. There has been no spend on consultancy fees during this period.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-09-05T15:54:03.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541149/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541149/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541149/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-20","Department for Exiting the European Union: Consultants and Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how much his Department has spent on consultancy and legal fees since it was established.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","43636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541150","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-05","<p>Britain has been at the forefront of the free trade-supporting countries in the EU for the last 40 years. The overall size and scope of the new department, including staffing and skill mix, are now under consideration. We will have the right resources in place so we can secure the best possible outcome for the UK as a whole.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","43808 ; 43809","2016-09-05T15:47:31.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541150/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541150/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541150/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-20","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many staff will be employed by his Department with the remit of renegotiating trading agreements with the EU.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","43637"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541151","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-05","<p>The new Department for Exiting the European Union will be made up of staff from various departments across Government, including from the UK’s Permanent Representation to the EU. The department has already started drawing together expertise from a wide range of departments where there is specific relevant knowledge. The overall size and scope of the new department, including staffing and budget, are now being considered – the department now has over 180 staff.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","43635 ; 43713 ; 43720","2016-09-05T16:03:44.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541151/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541151/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541151/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-20","Department for Exiting the European Union: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what the recruitment process is for employing an official from another government department in a new role in his Department.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","43634"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541152","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-05","<p>The new Department for Exiting the European Union will be made up of staff from various departments across Government, including from the UK’s Permanent Representation to the EU. The department has already started drawing together expertise from a wide range of departments where there is specific relevant knowledge. The overall size and scope of the new department, including staffing and budget, are now being considered – the department now has over 180 staff.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","43634 ; 43713 ; 43720","2016-09-05T16:03:45.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541152/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541152/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541152/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-20","Department for Exiting the European Union: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, how many officials from (a) the Foreign Office and (b) HM Treasury have (i) moved and (ii) are planning to move to work in his Department.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","43635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541153","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-05","<p>The Department is leading the UK’s negotiations to leave the European Union and establish the future relationship between the EU and the UK. We need a UK approach and clear objectives for negotiations. The process for leaving the EU and determining our future relationship will clearly not be brief or straightforward, so we need to take time to think through our objectives and approach.</p><p>The Government will ensure that the UK remains a world leader in international research collaboration, and will expect close collaboration between the UK and the EU in science to continue. UK businesses and universities should continue to bid for competitive EU funds while we remain a member of the EU. The Government will work with the European Commission to ensure payment when funds are awarded, and will underwrite the payment of such awards even when specific projects continue beyond the UK's departure from the EU.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-09-05T15:43:22.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541153/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541153/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541153/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-20","European Research Council","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what steps he plans to take during negotiations on leaving the EU to seek continued UK participation in the European Research Council after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","43587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541154","Department for Education","false","2016-09-09","<p>No discussions have taken place yet. There are no immediate changes following the EU Referendum, including in the circumstances of British citizens studying, or planning to study, in the EU.</p><p>Future arrangements for studying abroad will need to be considered as part of wider discussions about the UK’s relationship with the EU. For further information, see the Government Statement at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/statement-on-higher-education-and-research-following-the-eu-referendum" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/statement-on-higher-education-and-research-following-the-eu-referendum</a>.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-09-09T13:50:41.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541154/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541154/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541154/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-20","Students: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what discussions she has had with the European Commission on (a) the status of EU students at British universities and (b) the status of British students at universities within the EU; and whether it is her policy that such student will be eligible for international student fees once Britain has left the EU.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541155","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-13","<p>I have been in close contact with Commissioner Moedas on the topic of cross Europe research funding. The Commission have been very supportive of the UK perspective that while the UK remains a member of the EU, current EU funding and collaboration arrangements continue unchanged. And as we announced on the 13<sup>th</sup> August, the Treasury will underwrite funding for approved Horizon 2020 projects applied for before the UK leaves the European Union.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-09-13T15:09:52.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541155/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541155/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541155/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Research: EU Action","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with the European Commission on the status of British academics wishing to be included in cross-European research project applications funded by the EU.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541156","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-06","<p>Exit from the EU presents us with an opportunity under the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea to improve the way in which waters within the UK’s Exclusive Economic Zone are managed. Defra officials will be working with the new Department for Exiting the European Union, Devolved Administrations and stakeholders to develop proposals that will allow the UK to best take advantage of this opportunity.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-09-06T14:00:44.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541156/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541156/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541156/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-20","Fisheries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether the Government plans to seek to prohibit (a) non-UK-registered and (b) non-UK-owned fishing vessels from fishing within (i) UK territorial waters and (ii) the UK fisheries limits after the UK's exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","43586"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541157","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-06","<p>The Competition and Markets Authority works in cooperation with other competition authorities internationally on enforcement cases and other issues of mutual interest. It will continue to seek to work with other competition authorities in the future, where appropriate.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-09-06T13:15:58.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541157/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541157/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541157/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Competition: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what his policy is on future collaboration with the European Commission on competition enforcement and cooperation between the Competition and Markets Authority and the EU.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541158","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-05","<p>The UK remains a member of the EU until our withdrawal is completed. We will exercise our rights and meet our obligations as a member of the EU accordingly. Under Article 50 of the Treaty on European Union, the arrangements relating to the UK’s withdrawal are to be made between the UK and the EU.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-09-05T15:32:10.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541158/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541158/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541158/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-20","European Court of Justice: Judgements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has undertaken of the level of need to transfer European Court of Justice rulings into legislation to ensure their continued application in Britain after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541159","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-07","<p>The UK will continue to have all of the rights, obligations and benefits that membership brings, including receiving European funding, up until the point we leave the EU. The UK has not commenced negotiations for what happens after we leave the EU. At every step of the upcoming negotiations we will work to ensure the best possible outcome for the British people.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-09-07T13:16:19.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541159/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541159/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541159/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-20","Regional Planning and Development: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has held with the European Commission on whether the Commission will honour the full amounts of financial grants awarded for regional development in the most recent spending round.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541160","Department for International Trade","false","2016-09-09","<p>The UK has been a member of the World Trade Organisation (WTO) in its own right since the establishment of the WTO in 1995. The UK Ambassador and Permanent Representative to the WTO is currently Julian Braithwaite.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-09-09T12:20:11.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541160/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541160/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541160/answer",,,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-20","World Trade Organisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what preparations have been made for the UK having its own representative at the World Trade Organisation.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541161","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-07","<p>We are considering the detailed arrangements for ensuring that Parliament can provide proper scrutiny of any legislation resulting from our decision to leave the European Union and will be taking this forward with the administrations of both Houses.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-09-07T16:54:54.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541161/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541161/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541161/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-20","Parliamentary Scrutiny","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has held with administrations of the House and of the House of Lords on the capacity of Parliament to process additional legislation required as a result of the UK exiting the EU.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541162","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-05","<p>Two UK carbon capture and storage (CCS) projects have been allocated funding by the European Commission (Don Valley and White Rose); the status of this funding is subject to further discussions with the European Commission. The UK is also participating in a European Research Area Network (ERA-NET) on CCS under the Horizon 2020 programme. On 13 August 2016, the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) confirmed that the Government will underwrite certain EU funding, including approved Horizon 2020 research and development and innovation projects, regardless of the UK’s relationship with the EU.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-09-05T12:58:22.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541162/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541162/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541162/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Carbon Capture and Storage: EU Grants and Loans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of when the UK will lose EU funding previously allocated to the UK for carbon capture and storage programmes.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541163","Department of Health","false","2016-09-07","<p>As the Prime Minister stated on 20 July, as long as we are a member of the European Union we will respect the rights and obligations of EU membership, therefore the current arrangements remain in place. As we move to a new relationship with Europe, our guiding principle will be ensuring the best possible outcome for British people.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-09-07T12:29:57.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541163/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541163/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541163/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","Medical Treatments Abroad: Europe","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make it his policy to ensure that British citizens continue to be able to access healthcare on a reciprocal basis when visiting the EU.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43534"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541164","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-06","<p>Until exit negotiations are concluded, the UK remains a full member of the European Union and all the rights and obligations of EU membership remain in force.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2016-09-06T10:41:56.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541164/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541164/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541164/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-20","Mobile Phones: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if she will make it her policy to ensure that British residents continue to be able to be subject to caps on mobile telephone roaming charges when abroad after the UK leaves the EU; and what discussions she has had with (a) the European Commission and (b) the British telecommunications industry about achieving that aim.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541165","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-09-06","<p>Exit from the EU presents us with an opportunity under the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea to improve the way in which waters within the UK’s Exclusive Economic Zone are managed. Defra officials will be working with the new Department for Exiting the European Union, Devolved Administrations and stakeholders to develop proposals that will allow the UK to best take advantage of this opportunity.</p><p> </p><p>No formal discussions have taken place with the European Commission at this stage.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-09-06T13:54:26.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541165/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541165/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541165/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-20","Fish: Conservation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what her policy is on future collaboration with the EU on fish stock management; and what discussions she has had to date with the European Commission on that matter.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541166","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-05","<p>The UK’s commitment to tackling global climate change remains firm. We are committed to the UK Climate Change Act and the Paris Agreement, and have accepted the recommendation of the Committee on Climate Change on the fifth carbon budget.</p><p> </p><p>Until we leave the EU, the UK remains a Member State, with all of the rights and obligations this entails. We will therefore continue to participate in EU negotiations, including those on the EU’s climate framework up to 2030.</p><p> </p><p>It is not appropriate at this point to speculate about arrangements for after the UK ceases to be a Member State.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-09-05T12:58:52.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541166/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541166/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541166/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Climate Change","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the Government plans to continue its participation in the negotiations towards the 2030 EU Climate Framework; and whether the UK plans to commit to meeting the requirements of that framework after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541167","Department for Transport","false","2016-09-08","<p>While we remain a full member of the EU, we retain the same rights and obligations as all other Members, including those covered by the existing directives and regulations, such as rules on flight delays under EU Regulation 261/2004.</p><p> </p><p>The future application of this legislation will depend on the outcome of negotiating a new relationship with the EU.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2016-09-08T14:06:57.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541167/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541167/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541167/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-20","Aviation: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will make it his policy to ensure that British citizens continue to benefit from the rules on flight delays covered by EU Regulation 261/2004.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541168","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-06","<p>The Competition and Markets Authority has primary responsibility for enforcing competition law in the UK. Its primary duty is to seek to promote competition, both within and outside the UK, for the benefits of consumers.</p><p>At every step of the negotiations to withdraw from the European Union we will work to ensure the best possible outcome for the British people.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-09-06T13:16:33.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541168/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541168/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541168/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Competition: EU Internal Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the Government plans to take account of market operations across the current single market when enforcing competition and anti-trust policy after Britain exits the EU.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541169","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-05","<p>We will have the right resources in place so we can secure the best possible outcome for the UK as a whole, and will be taking advice from a variety of sources as we consider options, including on staffing and skill mix, for the new department.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker","43714","2016-09-05T15:28:46.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541169/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541169/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541169/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-20","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether his Department plans to commission professional service companies to assist with the negotiation process of exiting the EU.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541170","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-09-14","<p>There has been no decision on the future terms of trade for the UK. In preparation for negotiations to leave the EU, the Government is undertaking work across a range of areas, including market access, across all sectors.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-09-14T13:01:49.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541170/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541170/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541170/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Manufacturing Industries: Export Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will conduct an assessment on the potential effect on the manufacturing sector in Britain of reverting back to World Trade Organisation terms for exports.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541171","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-08","<p>While it is clear that we do now face a significant economic challenge as a result of the referendum decision, the UK economy is well placed to respond. HM Government is monitoring ongoing developments in the economy and the independent Office for Budget Responsibility will produce an updated economic forecast alongside the Autumn Statement 2016.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-09-08T10:45:49.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541171/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541171/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541171/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-20","Economic Situation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the consequences of the referendum result on (a) the British economy and (b) investment spending in the UK in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","43544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541172","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-09-05","<p>As we prepare for negotiations on the UK’s exit from the EU, we will continue to consult with a broad range of stakeholders within Government and beyond in order to secure the best possible deal for the whole UK.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-09-05T15:48:10.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541172/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541172/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541172/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-20","Iron and Steel: Manufacturing Industries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy on the future of the UK steel industry.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","43526"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541183","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-27","<p>The Government will publish its Rail Freight Strategy in due course.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-27T14:49:08.793Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541183/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541183/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541183/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-20","Railways: Freight","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they intend to publish their latest rail freight strategy.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL1347"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541184","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-27","<p>The Department for Transport is close to finalising its response to the Law Commission’s recommendations on the reform of level crossing legislation.</p><p> </p><p>This is a complex area and it has been necessary to explore all the available options in detail. Whilst this has taken time, I am confident that we will be able to come forward with proposals for a cohesive package of improvements shortly.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-27T14:48:56.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541184/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541184/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541184/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-20","Level Crossings","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they plan to implement the recommendations made by the Law Commission in 2013 regarding level crossing legislation.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL1348"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541185","Department of Health","false","2016-07-25","<p>It would not be possible or practical to monitor how individuals choose to access medicines or services outside of the National Health Service or to assess the impact on that individual. Registered pharmacies that operate online and that may supply drugs for use as pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) are the responsibility of the General Pharmaceutical Council. We are aware that some local authority commissioned sexual health services are offering monitoring of the pharmacological efficacy of generic PrEP however this is a matter for local decision.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL1350 ; HL1351","2016-07-25T10:46:08.027Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541185/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541185/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541185/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","HIV Infection: Drugs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Prior of Brampton on 13 July (HL1006), whether they have any plans to monitor private access to (1) Truvada for pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) from clinics within England, and (2) generic versions of Truvada for PrEP online from overseas.","false","Biography information for Lord Black of Brentwood",,"Lord Black of Brentwood","HL1349"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541186","Department of Health","false","2016-07-25","<p>It would not be possible or practical to monitor how individuals choose to access medicines or services outside of the National Health Service or to assess the impact on that individual. Registered pharmacies that operate online and that may supply drugs for use as pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) are the responsibility of the General Pharmaceutical Council. We are aware that some local authority commissioned sexual health services are offering monitoring of the pharmacological efficacy of generic PrEP however this is a matter for local decision.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL1349 ; HL1351","2016-07-25T10:46:08.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541186/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541186/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541186/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","HIV Infection: Drugs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the risks to individual and public health of significant numbers of individuals accessing generic versions of Truvada for pre-exposure prophylaxis online from overseas.","false","Biography information for Lord Black of Brentwood",,"Lord Black of Brentwood","HL1350"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541187","Department of Health","false","2016-07-25","<p>It would not be possible or practical to monitor how individuals choose to access medicines or services outside of the National Health Service or to assess the impact on that individual. Registered pharmacies that operate online and that may supply drugs for use as pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) are the responsibility of the General Pharmaceutical Council. We are aware that some local authority commissioned sexual health services are offering monitoring of the pharmacological efficacy of generic PrEP however this is a matter for local decision.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL1349 ; HL1350","2016-07-25T10:46:08.183Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541187/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541187/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541187/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","HIV Infection: Drugs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether individuals using generic versions of Truvada for pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) obtained online from overseas can access free at the point of need the appropriate monitoring and tests that are required, including as necessary tests for the pharmacological efficacy of the generic drugs they are taking, even though Truvada for PrEP has not been commissioned by NHS England.","false","Biography information for Lord Black of Brentwood",,"Lord Black of Brentwood","HL1351"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541188","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-08-03","<p>The Government does not keep records of numbers of animals that die as a result of being locked in cars. Records of prosecutions related to animals dying in vehicles would fall under the general offence of causing unnecessary suffering to an animal which do not provide details of individual cases.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL1353","2016-08-03T13:27:07.54Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541188/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541188/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541188/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-20","Domestic Animals: Animal Welfare","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they collect statistics on the number of domestic animals that die as a result of being locked in a car or other motor vehicle either because of lack of oxygen or from heat; and if so, how many such deaths were recorded in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Lord Black of Brentwood",,"Lord Black of Brentwood","HL1352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541189","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-08-03","<p>The Government does not keep records of numbers of animals that die as a result of being locked in cars. Records of prosecutions related to animals dying in vehicles would fall under the general offence of causing unnecessary suffering to an animal which do not provide details of individual cases.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble","HL1352","2016-08-03T13:27:07.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541189/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541189/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541189/answer",,,,,,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-07-20","Domestic Animals: Animal Welfare","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many prosecutions there have been in the last five years for cruelty to animals arising from the death of a domestic animal being locked in a car or other motor vehicle.","false","Biography information for Lord Black of Brentwood",,"Lord Black of Brentwood","HL1353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541190","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-08-02","<p>The UK opposes the death penalty in all circumstances and in every country, especially for crimes other than the most serious and for juveniles, in line with the minimum standards set out in the EU Guidelines on the Death Penalty of 2008 and the provisions of the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights and the Arab Charter on Human Rights.</p><p>We continue to raise the cases of Ali Al-Nimr, Dawood Al-Marhoon and Adullah Al-Zaher with the Saudi authorities at the highest levels, including during the former Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond)’s most recent visit to Saudi Arabia on 29 May. We expect that Ali Al-Nimr and the two others who were convicted as juveniles will not be executed.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","HL1355 ; HL1357","2016-08-02T13:53:09.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541190/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541190/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541190/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-20","Saudi Arabia: Capital Punishment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made to the government of Saudi Arabia about the use of the death penalty against minors.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Coventry",,"The Lord Bishop of Coventry","HL1354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541191","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-08-02","<p>The UK opposes the death penalty in all circumstances and in every country, especially for crimes other than the most serious and for juveniles, in line with the minimum standards set out in the EU Guidelines on the Death Penalty of 2008 and the provisions of the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights and the Arab Charter on Human Rights.</p><p>We continue to raise the cases of Ali Al-Nimr, Dawood Al-Marhoon and Adullah Al-Zaher with the Saudi authorities at the highest levels, including during the former Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond)’s most recent visit to Saudi Arabia on 29 May. We expect that Ali Al-Nimr and the two others who were convicted as juveniles will not be executed.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","HL1354 ; HL1357","2016-08-02T13:53:09.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541191/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541191/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541191/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-20","Saudi Arabia: Capital Punishment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have made this year to the government of Saudi Arabia regarding the use of beheading and crucifixion as criminal punishments.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Coventry",,"The Lord Bishop of Coventry","HL1355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541192","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-29","<p>We frequently raise religious freedom as part of our dialogue with the Saudi authorities on a wide range of human rights issues, including freedom of thought, conscience and religion. We pursue this dialogue though a variety of means, including diplomatic channels and Ministerial visits. The Saudi Arabian authorities are encouraging reforms at a pace that is acceptable to Saudi society.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-07-29T13:59:55.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541192/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541192/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541192/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-20","Saudi Arabia: Religious Freedom","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the levels of discrimination experienced by Shia citizens in Saudi Arabia in the fields of public education, government employment and religious freedom.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Coventry",,"The Lord Bishop of Coventry","HL1356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541193","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-08-02","<p>The UK opposes the death penalty in all circumstances and in every country, especially for crimes other than the most serious and for juveniles, in line with the minimum standards set out in the EU Guidelines on the Death Penalty of 2008 and the provisions of the International Covenant on Civil and Political Rights and the Arab Charter on Human Rights.</p><p>We continue to raise the cases of Ali Al-Nimr, Dawood Al-Marhoon and Adullah Al-Zaher with the Saudi authorities at the highest levels, including during the former Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond)’s most recent visit to Saudi Arabia on 29 May. We expect that Ali Al-Nimr and the two others who were convicted as juveniles will not be executed.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns","HL1354 ; HL1355","2016-08-02T13:53:09.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541193/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541193/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541193/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-20","Saudi Arabia: Capital Punishment","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the decision by the Specialised Criminal Court in Saudi Arabia to sentence Ali Mohammed Baqir Al-Nimr, Abdullah Al-Zaher and Dawood Al-Marhoon to death by crucifixion for seeking democratic reforms in that country.","false","Biography information for The Lord Bishop of Coventry",,"The Lord Bishop of Coventry","HL1357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541195","Department of Health","false","2016-08-02","<p>The Government bases its evaluation of vaccination programmes on the advice of the Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation (JCVI), other expert groups and evidence from a wide range of epidemiologists and other experts. Their considerations include the impact of rare diseases, immunisation, and impacts on children. The methodology used to assess cost-effectiveness of regular (i.e. non-emergency) immunisation programmes is based on published National Institute for Health and Care Excellence guidance <em>Guide to the methods of technology appraisal 2013</em>. A copy of the guidance is attached.</p><p> </p><p>The Cost Effectiveness Methodology for Immunisation Programmes and Procurements (CEMIPP) working group has reviewed whether any changes to the methodology might be appropriate for immunisation and the Government is considering the advice.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-08-02T13:14:37.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541195/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541195/answer","guide-to-the-methods-of-technology-appraisal-2013.pdf","Guide to the methods of technology appraisal 2013","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541195/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","Vaccination","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of how best to evaluate the impact of vaccination programmes to prevent rare diseases of high severity, and in particular the cost-effectiveness of the vaccination of children.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL1358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541196","Department of Health","false","2016-08-02","<p>No, the Terms of Reference have not changed.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-08-02T13:14:55.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541196/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541196/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541196/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","Vaccination","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the scope of the Cost Effectiveness Methodology for Immunisation Programmes and Procurements working group has shifted from its original purpose, and if so, why.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL1359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541197","Department of Health","false","2016-08-02","<p>The Department received the Cost Effectiveness Methodology for Immunisation Programmes and Procurements report on 20 July 2016. The report will be published in due course. A decision on consultation has not yet been made.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL1361","2016-08-02T13:15:09.653Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541197/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541197/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541197/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","Vaccination","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Cost Effectiveness Methodology for Immunisation Programmes and Procurements working group’s final report has been provided to the Department of Health, and if so, when that report will be published.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL1360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541198","Department of Health","false","2016-08-02","<p>The Department received the Cost Effectiveness Methodology for Immunisation Programmes and Procurements report on 20 July 2016. The report will be published in due course. A decision on consultation has not yet been made.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL1360","2016-08-02T13:15:09.727Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541198/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541198/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541198/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","Vaccination","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Cost Effectiveness Methodology for Immunisation Programmes and Procurements working group’s recommendations will be subject to public consultation, and if so, when.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL1361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541199","Department of Health","false","2016-08-02","<p>The report of the Cost Effectiveness Methodology for Immunisation Programmes and Procurement (CEMIPP) review was received in the Department on 20 July. The Department is considering this report and its potential implications.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL1363","2016-08-02T13:13:51.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541199/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541199/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541199/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the implications of the Joint Committee on Vaccination and Immunisation (JCVI) operating differently to other health technology assessment bodies, such as NICE, as stated in the minutes of the June JCVI meeting, in the event that the recommendations of the Cost Effectiveness Methodology for Immunisation Programmes and Procurements working group are adopted.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL1362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541200","Department of Health","false","2016-08-02","<p>The report of the Cost Effectiveness Methodology for Immunisation Programmes and Procurement (CEMIPP) review was received in the Department on 20 July. The Department is considering this report and its potential implications.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL1362","2016-08-02T13:13:51.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541200/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541200/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541200/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","Vaccination","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they will ensure consistency between the recommendations of the Cost Effectiveness Methodology for Immunisation Programmes and Procurements working group and those of the Department of Health’s Appraisal Alignment Working Group on similar issues.","false","Biography information for Lord Hunt of Kings Heath",,"Lord Hunt of Kings Heath","HL1363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541201","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-08-03","<p>The financial challenges faced by the Government means taking tough decisions on reducing public spending across a wide range of services.</p><p> </p><p>That is why the Government consulted on proposals to increase fees in asylum and immigration proceedings.</p><p> </p><p>Breaking down the data requested by quarter would incur disproportionate costs.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2016-08-03T15:47:52.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541201/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541201/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541201/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-20","Asylum and Immigration Tribunal: Fees and Charges","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why fees in the Asylum and Immigration Tribunal are to be increased, and what percentage of requests for a waiver of such fees were refused in each quarter since the beginning of 2015 to date.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL1364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541202","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-27","<p>I am withholding details of the date of the Mk 4A's component's entry into service, progress to date and the cost of the programme, for the purpose of safeguarding national security.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-07-27T13:15:48.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541202/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541202/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541202/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-20","Trident Missiles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the in-service date for the UK Trident Mark 4A nuclear warhead; what are the estimated costs of the Mark 4A programme; and what progress has been made to date in delivering that programme.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jolly",,"Baroness Jolly","HL1365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541203","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-27","<p>I refer the noble Baroness to the Written Ministerial Statement made by the Secretary of State for Defence (Michael Fallon) on 21 April 2016 (HCWS689). The contract between the Ministry of Defence (MOD) and the Atomic Weapons Establishment Management Limited (AWEML) has been reviewed. As a result of the review, the MOD has greater control over the programme, while ensuring that AWE continues to deliver value for money for the taxpayer. The contract between the MOD and AWEML also provides the opportunity for higher performance incentives, as well as reductions if targets are not met. These arrangements are now in force.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-07-27T13:15:28.937Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541203/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541203/answer","Hansard Extract 21 April 2016, HCWS689.docx","Atomic Weapons Establishment Contract.","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541203/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-20","AWE","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what new arrangements they plan to introduce for the delivery of the Nuclear Warhead Capability Sustainment Programme, and when those arrangements will enter into force.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jolly",,"Baroness Jolly","HL1366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541204","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-27","<p>The anticipated outturn costs cannot be provided. The current approved costs and in-service dates for Project Mensa and Project Pegasus are shown below.</p><p> </p><p>In-service dates are shown in bandings to avoid prejudice to national security and defence.</p><p> </p><p>The Main Gate business cases for Projects Mensa and Pegasus include estimates for risk and uncertainty, which are contained within the approved costs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Project</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>In-service period</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Approved cost (£million)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Project Mensa (warhead assembly/disassembly)</p></td><td><p>2016-20</p></td><td><p>734</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Project Pegasus (uranium components)</p></td><td><p>2016-20</p></td><td><p>634</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL1368","2016-07-27T13:43:30.34Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541204/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541204/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541204/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-20","AWE","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what are the current anticipated outturn costs and in-service dates for (1) Project Mensa, and (2) Project Pegasus, at the Atomic Weapons Establishment.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jolly",,"Baroness Jolly","HL1367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541205","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-27","<p>The anticipated outturn costs cannot be provided. The current approved costs and in-service dates for Project Mensa and Project Pegasus are shown below.</p><p> </p><p>In-service dates are shown in bandings to avoid prejudice to national security and defence.</p><p> </p><p>The Main Gate business cases for Projects Mensa and Pegasus include estimates for risk and uncertainty, which are contained within the approved costs.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Project</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>In-service period</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Approved cost (£million)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Project Mensa (warhead assembly/disassembly)</p></td><td><p>2016-20</p></td><td><p>734</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Project Pegasus (uranium components)</p></td><td><p>2016-20</p></td><td><p>634</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe","HL1367","2016-07-27T13:43:30.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541205/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541205/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541205/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-20","AWE","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much contingency funding has been allocated for (1) Project Mensa, and (2) Project Pegasus, at the Atomic Weapons Establishment.","false","Biography information for Baroness Jolly",,"Baroness Jolly","HL1368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541206","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-08-04","<p>SoftBank has made it clear that it intends to invest in ARM, keep its HQ in the UK, and at least double the employee headcount in the UK. The Government welcomes this. No rival bids for ARM have so far been made.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-08-04T12:20:55.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541206/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541206/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541206/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","ARM: Softbank","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they consulted experts in the field before publicly welcoming the acquisition of ARM Holdings by SoftBank, and whether they would similarly welcome a rival bid from an international private equity investor.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL1369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541207","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-08-30","<p>The Takeover Panel is responsible for enforcing the post offer undertakings given by SoftBank under the terms of the Takeover Code. Grant Thornton LLP has been appointed as an independent supervisor under the Code to monitor compliance with the undertakings. The Takeover Panel can require SoftBank to submit written progress reports in such form and as frequently as it requires and can take disciplinary action if the undertakings are not fulfilled. The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy will continue to monitor developments.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-08-30T13:25:30.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541207/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541207/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541207/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","ARM: Softbank","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they propose to enforce the commitments they have obtained from SoftBank in connection with employment and the location of the headquarters of ARM Holdings.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL1370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541208","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-08-15","<p>As we build an economy that works for all, the Government will keep the law on takeovers under constant review.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-08-15T12:25:07.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541208/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541208/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541208/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","Foreign Companies: Takeovers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to introduce legislation restricting the acquisition of key UK companies by foreign investors while they consider their industrial strategy.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL1371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541209","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-08-12","<p>It is for the parties to the proposed transaction to consider their relative positions in compliance with the Takeover Code. The board of the target company must take independent advice on the offer, and evaluate its effects on the company’s interests, before giving the board’s opinion to shareholders.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-08-12T08:33:57.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541209/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541209/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541209/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-20","ARM: Softbank","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what powers they have to review the financial capacity of SoftBank to support ARM Holdings, and in particular whether they can require a further injection of capital into ARM Holdings before any takeover occurs.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL1372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541210","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-29","<p>The government welcomes the European Commission’s commitment to publish a legislative proposal on a recovery and resolution framework for central counterparties (CCPs) and will assess the proposals once published. Given the global nature of CCPs, the recovery and resolution framework will need to take into account ongoing work by the Financial Stability Board, the Committee on Payments and Market Infrastructures (CPMI) and the International Organization of Securities Commissions (IOSCO).</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2016-07-29T12:19:49.783Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541210/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541210/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541210/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-20","Financial Institutions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the proposed EU-wide recovery and resolution frameworks for failed central counterparties, and whether in their assessment there are any outstanding issues.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL1373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541211","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-29","<p>LCH.Clearnet Ltd, LCH.Clearnet SA, Eurex Clearing and CC&amp;G are separate CCPs regulated under European Regulation No 648/2012 (EMIR) by their respective regulators. The London Stock Exchange Group and Deutsche Borse have publicly stated their intention that “[t]he existing regulatory framework of all regulated entities within the Combined Group would remain unchanged” following the merger. Once notified by the companies of their proposal to merge, the Bank of England will assess the proposal for a change in control of LCH.Clearnet Ltd in line with the criteria set out in EMIR.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2016-07-29T12:19:14.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541211/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541211/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541211/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-20","London Stock Exchange: Deutsche Borse","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the consequences for financial stability of combining four large central counterparties (CCPs), LCH.Clearnet Ltd, LCH.Clearnet SA, Eurex and CC&amp;G, when the London Stock Exchange and Deutsche Borse merge; whether adequate recovery and resolution frameworks will be in place for each of these CCPs; and whether those frameworks will be ring-fenced from each other.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL1374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541212","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-08-10","<p>We will make a success out of leaving the European Union. We will protect and strengthen the national interest.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-08-10T11:03:39.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541212/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541212/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541212/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-20","Brexit","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether it is their position that leaving the EU is in the British national interest.","false","Biography information for Lord Tebbit",,"Lord Tebbit","HL1375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541213","Cabinet Office","true","2016-08-03","<p>In the present Government there are five unpaid Ministers who are members of the House of Lords and three unpaid Ministers who are members of the House of Commons.</p>",,"Earl of Courtown",,"2016-08-03T13:48:50.577Z","2016-08-03T13:57:24.903Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541213/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541213/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541213/answer",,,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541213/answer/previousversion/8779","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541213/answer/previousversion/8779","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-20","Ministers: Pay","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many ministers (1) in the House of Lords, and (2) in the House of Commons, are presently unpaid.","false","Biography information for Lord Trefgarne",,"Lord Trefgarne","HL1376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541214","Cabinet Office","false","2016-08-03","<p>Government has been working closely with the BBC to ensure the requirements of the MOD, FCO, Cabinet Office, and the intelligence agencies can continue to be met by BBC Monitoring.</p>",,"Earl of Courtown",,"2016-08-03T13:45:03.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541214/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541214/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541214/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-20","BBC Monitoring","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the response by Lord Ashton of Hyde on 19 July (HL Deb, col 525), what assessment the Foreign and Commonwealth Office, Ministry of Defence, National Security Council, Joint Intelligence Committee and National Crime Agency have made of the suitability of the planned changes to the provision of reporting by the BBC Monitoring Service.","false","Biography information for Lord West of Spithead",,"Lord West of Spithead","HL1377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541215","Department for Education","false","2016-08-03","<p>The Advisory Committee on Degree Awarding Powers (ACDAP) does not consider applications for university title. In the period 2013-2016, there have been two applications for degree awarding powers that did not proceed to full scrutiny of their application because of ACDAP’s preliminary judgement and feedback. One application was from a publicly funded provider and one was from a private for profit provider.</p>",,"Earl of Courtown",,"2016-08-03T15:47:31.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541215/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541215/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541215/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-20","Degrees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, between 2013 and 2016 inclusive, how many institutions applied to the Quality Assurance Agency’s Advisory Committee on Degree Awarding Powers (ACDAP) with a view to obtaining (1) degree awarding powers, and (2) university title, but did not proceed to full scrutiny of their applications because of the ACDAP’s preliminary judgment and feedback; and of those, how many were (a) public or not-for-profit institutions, and (b) private for-profit providers.","false","Biography information for Baroness Wolf of Dulwich",,"Baroness Wolf of Dulwich","HL1378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541216","Cabinet Office","false","2016-09-28","<p>Appointments of Government Ministers and the Lord Chancellor are for the Prime Minister to recommend to Her Majesty. I would note that Section 2 of the 2005 Act explicitly states that the Prime Minister may take into account experience as a Minister of the Crown and as a member of either House of Parliament when deciding whether a person is qualified by experience to be Lord Chancellor.</p><p>I would also refer the noble peer to the speech by the Lord Chief Justice at the swearing in of the Lord Chancellor, which provides background on the Lord Chancellor’s experience, but also the historical context of those who have had custody of the Great Seal of the Realm, including its first female keeper back in 1253.</p><p><a href="https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/lcj-speech-swearing-in-lord-chancellor-july2016.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/wp-content/uploads/2016/07/lcj-speech-swearing-in-lord-chancellor-july2016.pdf</a></p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-09-28T15:10:59.28Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541216/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541216/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541216/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-20","Lord Chancellor","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government to what extent the new Lord Chancellor meets the criteria for appointment laid down in the Constitutional Reform Act 2005.","false","Biography information for Lord Lexden",,"Lord Lexden","HL1379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541217","Home Office","false","2016-07-29","<p>The 2011 Prevent strategy and statutory guidance on the exercise of the Prevent duty both contain glossaries which explain the meaning of terms used.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-29T12:18:06.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541217/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541217/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541217/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-20","Radicalism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the reply by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 27 June (HL Deb, col 1352), what assessment they have made of whether action to combat the threat of terrorism could be helped by a clearer use of language, for example by explaining the actual meaning of words such as "extremism", "radicalisation", and "fundamentalism".","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL1380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541219","Home Office","false","2016-07-29","<p>As part of the Government’s counter-terrorism strategy (CONTEST), the Prevent strategy was revised in 2011 to address all forms of terrorism.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-29T12:27:00.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541219/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541219/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541219/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-20","Radicalism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the reply by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 27 June (HL Deb, col 1352), whether when they use the words "extremism", "radicalisation" and "fundamentalism" they are usually referring to extreme, radical or fundamental Islam; and if not, to what they are referring.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL1381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541220","Home Office","false","2016-07-27","<p>Tackling cases of child sexual exploitation, including those that have occurred in Rotherham, is a top priority for this Government. People who abuse children must be stopped – their race, age or gender is irrelevant.</p><p>Child sexual exploitation is not exclusive to any single culture, community, race or religion.</p><p>The previous Home Secretary launched the report ‘Tackling Child Sexual Exploitation’ in March 2015. This report sets out a national response to the failures we have seen in Rotherham and elsewhere, where children were let down by the very people who were responsible for protecting them.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-27T13:31:04.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541220/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541220/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541220/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-20","Offences against Children: Rotherham","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the reply by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 27 June (HL Deb, col 1352), what assessment they have made of whether, when referring to cases such as the Rotherham sexual abuse case, it is more accurate and appropriate to refer to the perpetrators as "Muslim" or "Islamist", rather than as "Asian".","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL1382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541221","Home Office","false","2016-08-03","<p>The Syrian Vulnerable Person’s Resettlement Scheme prioritises the most vulnerable Syrian refugees, including families with dependent children of any age. Of the 1,602 Syrians who arrived between October 2015 and March 2016, around half were aged under 18. The Vulnerable Children’s Resettlement Scheme, announced in April, will resettle vulnerable children under the age of 18 from the Middle East and North Africa region, with their families or carers where appropriate. One of the reasons for creating the scheme was to allow the inclusion of children at risk from nationalities other than Syrian, including, for example, Yazidis from Iraq.</p><p>For both schemes, we work closely with the UNHCR, who identify refugees for resettlement using their established vulnerability criteria rather than seeking to include children of a particular age. While membership of a minority religion is not in itself one of the vulnerability criteria, members of minority religions may qualify under one of the vulnerability headings. It is important that we base our selection criteria on those most in need, rather than on the basis of membership of a particular religious group.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-08-03T13:44:25.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541221/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541221/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541221/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-20","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the average age of the child refugees they propose to take in from the conflicts in Syria and North Africa; what assessment they have made of the dominant religion of those children; whether it is their policy that priority should be given to Christian children; and, if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL1383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541222","Home Office","false","2016-08-03","<p>The definition of extremism is set out in the Counter-Extremism Strategy published on 19 October 2015 and is: ‘The vocal or active opposition to our fundamental values, including democracy, the rule of law, individual liberty and the mutual respect and tolerance of different faiths and beliefs. We also regard calls for the death of members of the armed forces as extremist.’ This definition covers both violent and non-violent extremism.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-08-03T13:27:32.133Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541222/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541222/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541222/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-20","Radicalism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress they have made in clarifying their definition of "non-violent extremism".","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL1384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541223","Home Office","false","2016-07-29","<p>As the Prevent Strategy explicitly states the Government is absolutely committed to protecting freedom of speech. Section 31 of the Counter-Terrorism &amp; Security Act 2015, for example includes specific protection for universities in this regard, and statutory guidance for schools makes the Prevent duty affirm our commitment that schools should be safe spaces in which children and young people can understand and discuss sensitive issues.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-29T12:27:25.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541223/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541223/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541223/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-20","Counter-terrorism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, under their counter-terrorism policy, it is acceptable to debate the nature of, and to criticise, all religions, including Islam, even if those arguments or criticisms offend adherents to those religions; and if not, whether they plan to clarify any limits on freedom of speech that that policy might impose.","false","Biography information for Lord Pearson of Rannoch",,"Lord Pearson of Rannoch","HL1385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541224","Department of Health","false","2016-07-26","<p>This information is not available in the format requested.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-07-26T13:19:32.573Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541224/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541224/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541224/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-20","Female Genital Mutilation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many women have been admitted to hospital in England and Wales as a result of female genital mutilation in each year between 2010 and 2015.","false","Biography information for Lord Smith of Hindhead",,"Lord Smith of Hindhead","HL1386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541225","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-08-03","<p>This information is not held centrally and can only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>",,"Earl of Courtown",,"2016-08-03T15:08:01.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541225/answer","Biography information for The Earl of Courtown","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541225/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541225/answer",,,,,,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-07-20","Motorways: Driving Offences","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many motorists have been prosecuted for the inconsiderate use of the middle lane on the motorway network since the announcement that the police would take appropriate action to discourage such behaviour.","false","Biography information for Lord Snape",,"Lord Snape","HL1387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541226","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-26","<p>Continuity of water supply to the West Bank is essential for both the basic needs of Palestinians and for stability and security more widely. The UK regularly raises the issue of water in the Occupied Palestinian Territories with the Palestinian Authority and Government of Israel. We encourage both parties to find a swift resolution to this issue and to reconvene the Joint Water Committee.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-07-26T15:33:43.7Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541226/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541226/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541226/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-20","Palestinians: Water Supply","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Verma on 7 July 2016 (HL799), what discussion they have had with the Palestinian Authority about its non-attendance at meetings with Israeli officials on the Joint Water Committee.","false","Biography information for Lord Turnberg",,"Lord Turnberg","HL1388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541227","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-29","<p>The information requested in relation to the evaluation of comments and forecasts about the UK could only be provided at disproportionate cost. However, the Independent Evaluation Office of the IMF produce a report evaluating the forecasts of the organisation and the most recent one was published in 2014.</p><p> </p><p>The UK economy is assessed by the IMF on an annual basis as part of the Article IV process. The IMF also produce quarterly forecasts for the UK economy in their World Economic Outlook (WEO) reports and WEO Updates.</p><p> </p><p>Article IV reports and World Economic Outlooks and Updates are readily available on the IMF website and include recent revisions to forecasts.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2016-07-29T12:21:02.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541227/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541227/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541227/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-20","International Monetary Fund","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many International Monetary Fund (IMF) reports have, since 2006, (1) commented on the state of the UK economy; (2) commented on the state of the UK economy and have been shown to be erroneous; and (3) made comments on the state of the UK economy that the IMF have had to revise or retract due to the inaccuracy of the forecast.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL1389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541228","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-08-10","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union will be made up of staff from various departments across Government, including from the UK’s Permanent Representation to the EU.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-08-10T13:56:36.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541228/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541228/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541228/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-20","Department for Exiting the European Union: Departmental Responsibilities","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to transfer operational command and control of the EU units from all other departments to the Department for Exiting the European Union.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL1390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541229","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-08-10","<p>The UK remains a member of the EU until our withdrawal is completed. We will exercise our rights and meet our obligations as a member of the EU accordingly.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","HL1392","2016-08-10T11:04:05.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541229/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541229/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541229/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-20","European Court of Justice","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to suspend immediately the implementation of all pending and future judgments of the European Court of Justice.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL1391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541230","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-08-10","<p>The UK remains a member of the EU until our withdrawal is completed. We will exercise our rights and meet our obligations as a member of the EU accordingly.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley","HL1391","2016-08-10T11:04:05.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541230/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541230/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541230/answer",,,,,,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-07-20","EU Action","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to suspend immediately all processes for passing into UK law all pending and future EU Directives and Regulations.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL1392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541231","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-27","<p>Prosecuting authorities from across Europe are liaising and coordinating their investigations through Eurojust. The Department for Transport is engaged in this process and is considering all possible options to reach a resolution on this issue.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-27T14:49:55.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541231/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541231/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541231/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-20","Volkswagen","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the investigations into diesel emissions by Volkswagen vehicles conducted by prosecutors in Germany and the US Department of Justice, what action they are taking to pursue any compensation and recompense that may be sought by UK consumers, and whether they plan to support any joint legal action against Volkswagen.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL1393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541232","Home Office","false","2016-07-29","<p>The Home Office has not made any such estimate. The costs of individual deployments are operational matters for individual chief constables, working with their democratically elected Police and Crime Commissioners.</p><p>The 2016-17 funding settlement for the police ensures that the police have adequate funding to do their work.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-29T12:03:17.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541232/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541232/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541232/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-20","Civil Disorder: Greater London","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the cost of policing the disturbance in Hyde Park and Marble Arch on the evening of 19 July.","false","Biography information for Lord Rogan",,"Lord Rogan","HL1394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541233","The Lord Chairman of Committees","false","2016-08-01","<p>All users of the Parliamentary Network are informed about the Acceptable User Policy every time they log on. Members are also asked to confirm that they have read and agree to the terms of the Acceptable Use Policy on hardware request forms.</p>",,"Lord Laming",,"2016-08-01T15:33:25.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541233/answer","Biography information for Lord Laming","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541233/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541233/answer",,,,,,,,,"200",,"Chairman of Committees (HoL)","2016-07-20","Peers: Email","2","House of Lords","To ask the Chairman of Committees, further to his Written Answer on 14 July (HL958) concerning the Parliamentary Digital Service, how members of the House are informed of the Acceptable Use Policy regarding using the Parliamentary Network.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL1395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541234","The Lord Chairman of Committees","false","2016-08-01","<p>Authorised personnel from the Digital Service manage the MessageLabs service.</p>",,"Lord Laming",,"2016-08-01T15:33:49.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541234/answer","Biography information for Lord Laming","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541234/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541234/answer",,,,,,,,,"200",,"Chairman of Committees (HoL)","2016-07-20","Peers: Email","2","House of Lords","To ask the Chairman of Committees, further to his Written Answer on 14 July (HL958) concerning the Parliamentary Digital Service, which Parliamentary officials or employees are authorised to manage the MessageLabs service contracted by the Parliamentary Digital Service.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL1396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541235","The Lord Chairman of Committees","false","2016-08-03","<p>The Acceptable Use Policy for Lords Members and staff is available on the intranet (<a href="https://intranet.parliament.uk/Documents/computers-equipment/Working-securely/Good-digital-citizen/Acceptable%20Use%20Policy%20v1.2.pdf" target="_blank">https://intranet.parliament.uk/Documents/computers-equipment/Working-securely/Good-digital-citizen/Acceptable%20Use%20Policy%20v1.2.pdf</a>) and at the Digital Service Drop-in. A very similar policy is in place for MPs; the Digital Service is currently working on a single Acceptable Use Policy.</p>",,"Lord Laming",,"2016-08-03T13:46:48.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541235/answer","Biography information for Lord Laming","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541235/answer","Acceptable Use Policy.pdf","Acceptable Use Policy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541235/answer",,,,,,,,,"200",,"Chairman of Committees (HoL)","2016-07-20","Peers: Email","2","House of Lords","To ask the Chairman of Committees whether he will place in the Library of the House a copy of the Acceptable Use Policy or policies for Parliamentary emails.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL1397"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541240","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-06","<p>The information requested in not held centrally.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","43704","2016-09-06T11:07:22.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541240/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541240/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541240/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-20","Film: Directors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what proportion of films backed by UK-based public funding bodies have been directed by women in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","43702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541241","HM Treasury","false","2016-09-09","<p>In 2014-15, there were 530 claims for film tax relief for an amount of £304 million. In 2015-16, there were 325 claims for film tax for an amount of £185 million – however, this is a provisional figure which will be revised upwards as claims continue to be submitted to HMRC.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC published statistics for the Creative Industries tax reliefs on 20 July 2016, including the number and amounts of claims for film tax relief. The statistics cover all years since the relief was introduced and can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/creative-industries-statistics-july-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/creative-industries-statistics-july-2016</a></p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-09-09T10:44:56.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541241/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541241/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541241/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-20","Film: Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much was claimed in film tax relief in each year of its operation.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","43703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541243","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-09-06","<p>The information requested in not held centrally.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","43702","2016-09-06T11:07:22.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541243/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541243/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541243/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-20","Film: Directors","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what the cash value of support from the public purse for films directed by women was in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","43704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541244","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-05","<p>The Royal Navy recognises the potential benefits from the use of unmanned vehicles in both air and sea environments and continues to explore how such systems can further augment its capabilities, although no decisions on future systems have yet been taken.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-09-05T14:52:45.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541244/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541244/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541244/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-20","Unmanned Air Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how he plans to ensure that the Royal Navy maintains its maritime unmanned air system capability from late 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","43696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541245","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-08","<p>The Ministry of Defence (MOD) spent £8.8 billion on single source contracts in the Financial Year 2015-16. This represents 25% of the Defence budget for that year.</p><p>The MOD regularly publishes statistics on defence expenditure and the latest data can be found at the following link:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/548285/Commentary_relating_to_Finance-Economics_Annual_Statistical_Bulletin_Trade-Industry-Contracts_2016-a.pdf</p><p> </p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-09-08T13:55:54.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541245/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541245/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541245/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-20","Defence: Procurement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of the defence budget was spent on single-source contracts in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","43697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541246","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-05","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer given by my predecessor (Philip Dunne) to Question 40451 to the hon. Member for Glasgow South West (Chris Stephens).</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-09-05T14:59:07.78Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541246/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541246/answer","20160627_QnA_extract_on_Warships_Antisubmarine_Warfare.docx","QnA extract on Warships: Antisubmarine Warfare","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541246/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-20","Frigates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what assessment he has made of the range of capability requirements for the General Purpose Frigate programme and the likely threats it will face.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","43694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541247","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-05","<p>The Department has implemented an action plan to improve compliance with IFRIC 4/IAS 17 for new contracts which are single contracts and impact a single site, with effect from 2016-17. This work should enable further understanding of the challenges and resources required to improve compliance. The Department will review the results of this exercise during 2016-17 before considering whether it can be expanded further.</p>","Sevenoaks","Michael Fallon",,"2016-09-05T14:42:12.95Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541247/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541247/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541247/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-20","Ministry of Defence: Accountancy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the qualification of his Department's 2015-16 accounts by the Comptroller and Auditor General, what steps is he taking to improve compliance by his Department with international accounting requirements for leases.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","43695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541248","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-05","<p>The UK's Vanguard Class submarines will begin to leave service by the early 2030s as the Successor submarines are introduced into service. I am withholding their respective planned out-of-service and in-service dates for the purpose of safeguarding national security.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","43681","2016-09-05T14:40:16.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541248/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541248/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541248/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-20","Trident Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, when the first Vanguard successor submarine will come into service.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","43675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541249","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-07","<p>The Ministry of Defence does not compile this information and to do so would incur disproportionate cost. While the Department encourages it's key suppliers to sub-contract UK companies in the supply chain, it is their responsibility to select individual sub-contractors.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-09-07T14:28:27.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541249/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541249/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541249/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-20","Trident Submarines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what proportion of the supply chain for the Vanguard-successor programme will be procured from the UK.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","43685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541250","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-09-05","<p>Sir John Parker, the Independent Chair of the National Shipbuilding Strategy, has had bilateral meetings with a significant number of key Government officials and Ministers, as well as with a broad range of maritime industry leaders and the Trades Unions (Confederation of Shipbuilding Engineering Unions, Unite and GMB).</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-09-05T14:59:44.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541250/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541250/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/541250/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-20","Warships: Shipbuilding","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, who has been consulted in drawing up the National Shipbuilding Strategy.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","43686"
