nd country of domicile of individuals taking out student loans for higher education, and, if so, how many people took out loans in each year since 2010, broken down by nationality.","false","Biography information for Baroness Wolf of Dulwich",,"Baroness Wolf of Dulwich","HL1338"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539177","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-29","<p>The UK will attend the State Department Consultation on Threats to Religious and Ethnic Minorities under Daesh on 28 and 29 July. It will be represented by a senior official from the Foreign and Commonwealth Office. The consultation will be used to discuss what countries are doing to protect minorities under Daesh and what more can be done. As the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson) made clear during his visit to Washington on 21 July, the Government is fully committed to working with international partners to ensure Daesh is held to account for its crimes.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-07-29T13:58:37.097Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539177/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539177/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539177/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","Islamic State","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to participate in the conference about the attacks on Yazidis, Christians and others by ISIS organised by the US State Department in Washington DC on 29 July; if so, who will represent them and whether whilst attending that conference they will explain why they have not supported the genocide declarations passed by the House of Commons and the US Congress.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1254"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539178","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-29","<p>This Government shares the House of Commons’ condemnation of Daesh atrocities against all civilians, including Christians, Mandeans, Yazidis, and other minorities, as well as the majority Muslim population in Iraq and Syria who continue to bear the brunt of Daesh’s brutality.</p><p> </p><p>It is a long-standing Government policy that any judgements on whether genocide has occurred are a matter for the international judicial system rather than governments or other non-judicial bodies. Our approach is to seek an end to all violations, and to prevent their further escalation, irrespective of whether these violations fit the definition of specific international crimes.</p><p> </p><p>We are fully committed to working internationally to ensure Daesh is held to account for its crimes. Ultimately, the best way of preventing future atrocities is to defeat Daesh and its violent ideology. That is why the UK is playing a leading role in the Global Coalition of more than 66 countries and international organisations united to defeat Daesh.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-07-29T14:00:43.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539178/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539178/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539178/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","Islamic State","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they now recognise that a genocide is underway against minorities in Syria and Iraq; and whether the opinion set out in <i>The Sunday Telegraph</i> on 27 March that ISIS "are engaged in what can only be called genocide of the poor Yazidis" by the new Foreign Secretary reflects their official position.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1255"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539179","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-29","<p>Rwanda is not a State party to the International Criminal Court (ICC). It is important that fugitives from international justice do not enjoy impunity and we note the UN Security Council Resolution (UNSCR 1593) has urged all States to cooperate fully with the ICC and its Prosecutor with regards to the situation in Darfur. We continue to follow closely developments in the ICC, including the level of States’ cooperation with the Court, and will consider further measures as appropriate.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-07-29T12:48:42.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539179/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539179/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539179/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","Omar al-Bashir","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have held with the government of Rwanda about the visit to that country by Omar al Bashir, President of Sudan, who has been indicted by the International Criminal Court for genocide and crimes against humanity.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1256"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539180","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-29","<p>We have not held any discussions with the Secretary General of the Commonwealth on this matter. However we continue to believe that State cooperation, in particular with respect to enforcement of arrest warrants is vital for the International Criminal Court to be effective in fulfilling its mandate to achieve justice for the victims of atrocities. We look forward to future meetings and discussions with the Secretary General on shared priorities for the Commonwealth.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-07-29T12:48:13.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539180/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539180/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539180/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","Omar al-Bashir","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have held with the Secretary General of the Commonwealth about recent visits to Rwanda and Uganda by Omar al Bashir, President of Sudan, who has been indicted by the International Criminal Court for genocide and crimes against humanity.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1257"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539181","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-29","<p>The International Criminal Court (ICC) has an established procedure for dealing with instances of non-cooperation and reports regularly to the UN Security Council on this matter. We continue to follow closely developments in the ICC, including the level of States’ cooperation with the Court, and will consider further measures as appropriate.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-07-29T12:47:43.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539181/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539181/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539181/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","Crimes against Humanity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration they have given to the imposition of sanctions and penalties on countries that host visits by those indicted for genocide or crimes against humanity such as Omar al Bashir, President of Sudan; and what discussions they have had with other signatories to the creation of the International Criminal Court about that issue.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1258"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539182","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-08-01","<p>The International Criminal Court (ICC) has an established procedure for dealing with instances of non-cooperation and reports regularly to the UN Security Council on this matter. We continue to follow closely developments in the ICC, including the level of States’ cooperation with the Court, and will consider further measures as appropriate.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-08-01T14:13:21.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539182/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539182/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539182/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","Crimes against Humanity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to table a resolution for discussion at the UN Security Council drawing attention to the failure of member states to assist the International Criminal Court in bringing to justice those indicted for war crimes, crimes against humanity, or genocide.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL1259"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539183","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-26","<p>The Red Arrows did not offer to make any changes to their original, approved routine or display sequence. However, they did liaise with the event organisers, who are responsible for mitigating risks to those on the ground and those in boats in the local estuary, on where best to locate the display. To avoid flying over anyone in the estuary, the Red Arrows were prepared to display over the sea.</p><p>The Red Arrows did not receive any safety advice specifically relating to a display at Fowey Regatta.</p><p> </p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-07-26T15:25:57.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539183/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539183/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539183/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-18","Red Arrows","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Earl Howe on 12 July (HL921), what changes the Red Arrows offered to make to their original programme; and what, if any, safety advice was received by the Red Arrows and from whom.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL1260"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539184","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-21","<p>The Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA) will not be instituting any prosecution following the collapse of the mezzanine deck on the ST HELEN ferry at Fishbourne, Isle of Wight.</p><p> </p><p>Before a prosecution is commenced the matter must pass the two stage test as outlined in the Code for Crown Prosecutors. The MCA has confirmed that it will not pass both stages and have decided that it would not be in the public interest to pursue this further at this time.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-21T13:38:15.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539184/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539184/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539184/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-18","Ferries: Isle of Wight","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon on 6 May (HL7878), when the Marine and Coastguard Agency will institute a prosecution of those responsible for that incident.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL1261"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539185","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-08-01","<p>The UK Government takes the protection of people’s personal data very seriously. The handling and sharing of personal data is primarily governed by the Data Protection Act 1998 (DPA), which establishes a legal framework of rights and obligations that protect individuals’ personal information.</p><p> </p><p>The Information Commissioner’s Office, who is the independent regulatory body responsible for enforcing the DPA in the UK, has produced the guidance for the general public on such matters. This guidance can be found on its’ website at; <a href="http://www.ico.org.uk/for-the-public/is-my-%20information-being-handled-correctly/" target="_blank">www.ico.org.uk/for-the-public/is-my- information-being-handled-correctly/</a></p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2016-08-01T14:14:50.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539185/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539185/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539185/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-18","Home Shopping","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what regulations protect the contact details of vulnerable people being passed to other commercial agencies when purchasing a product online or having one purchased on their behalf.","false","Biography information for Baroness Finlay of Llandaff",,"Baroness Finlay of Llandaff","HL1262"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539186","Home Office","false","2016-07-29","<p>We are reviewing our process for dealing with applications for refugee family reunion in consultation with the Foreign and Commonwealth Office and the Ministry of Justice. We are working closely with the British Red Cross and are considering the recommendations made in the Not So Straightforward report in detail.</p><p>We have now improved our guidance on processing family reunion applications so that it is clear, consistent and accessible. We intend to publish this in the next few weeks. We have also committed to redesigning the application form to ensure that applicants better understand the process and what is required of them.</p><p>There are no plans to extend the family reunion criteria as called for in the British Red Cross Torn Apart campaign. The current family reunion policy meets our international obligations and strikes the right balance. Where family members cannot meet the requirements of the Immigration Rules, such as in the case of an 18 year old applying to join their refugee parents in the UK, we consider whether there are exceptional circumstances or compassionate reasons to justify granting entry clearance outside the Rules.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-29T12:14:11.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539186/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539186/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539186/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Refugees: Families","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the British Red Cross report <i>Not So Straightforward</i> and its campaign to reunite refugee families, <i>Torn Apart</i>.","false","Biography information for Lord Hylton",,"Lord Hylton","HL1263"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539188","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-26","<p>The information is set out in the table below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Date</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Privy Counsellors</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>13th July 2016</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>657</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Appointments since 11th May 2010</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>179</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-07-26T13:11:18.06Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539188/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539188/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539188/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-18","Privy Council","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what was the size of the Privy Council on 13 July; and how many appointments had been made to it up to that date since 11 May 2010.","false","Biography information for Lord Lexden",,"Lord Lexden","HL1264"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539189","Home Office","false","2016-07-29","<p>The five strands of monitored hate crime (race, religion, sexual orientation transgender identity and disability) are the minimum categories that police officers and staff are ex-pected to record. There are, however, many other groups in society who have been targeted with hostility and crime. Any specific incidents of Hate Crime are an operational matter for the police.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-29T12:15:26.163Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539189/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539189/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539189/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Hate Crime: Nottinghamshire","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the authority of Nottinghamshire Police to categorise wolf-whistling as a hate crime rather than a public nuisance; and whether they consider that such a decision may derogate from the seriousness of classification of hate crime.","false","Biography information for Lord Maginnis of Drumglass",,"Lord Maginnis of Drumglass","HL1265"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539190","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-08-01","<p>The right approach is to allow the Pensions Regulator to get on with its investigations into the use of its anti-avoidance powers. There is a clear legal process that must be followed and this can sometimes take a considerable amount of time. The Pensions Regulator’s Chief Executive has given a commitment that it will have made significant progress by the end of 2016. It has said that when it becomes appropriate to do so it will consider publishing a report of the case under Section 89 of the Pensions Act 2004. The Regulator is independent and Ministers cannot become involved in its decisions on whether or not to exercise its powers or seek to influence its investigations in any way.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-08-01T15:34:35.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539190/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539190/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539190/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-18","British Home Stores: Pensions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what discussions they have had with the Pensions Regulator about the length of time it will require to report on the BHS pension scheme; and whether they plan to communicate that information to fund managers.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL1266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539191","Department for International Trade","false","2016-07-25","<p>My right hon. Friend the Prime Minister has created the Department for International Trade, which is responsible for promoting British trade across the world and ensuring the UK takes advantage of the huge opportunities open to us. We are building up our trade policy capability. ​The Department has begun a process to recruit and train staff to work on the UK’s trade policy. We will adapt the resource devoted to trade policy in line with future demands.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Price",,"2016-07-25T14:12:13.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539191/answer","Biography information for Lord Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539191/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539191/answer",,,,,,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-07-18","Trade Agreements","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to establish a scheme to retrain as trade negotiators people with experience of high level intergovernmental and global institutional practice.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL1267"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539192","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-26","<p>In response to the 'Get Well Plan' agreed with the Secretary of State for Defence in February, CarillionAmey's performance has improved. The Ministry of Defence (MOD) is now seeking assurances that the performance improvements made are sustainable over the life of the contracts for which CarillionAmey is responsible. The MOD will continue to prepare contingency plans, for potential termination, in the event that sustained improvements are not made.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-07-26T15:29:43.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539192/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539192/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539192/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-18","Armed Forces: Housing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they plan to terminate the contract with CarillionAmey for service family accommodation, and if so, what plans they have for the service to be provided in-house.","false","Biography information for Lord Richards of Herstmonceux",,"Lord Richards of Herstmonceux","HL1268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539193","Ministry of Defence","false","2016-07-26","<p>We are studying the report of the Iraq Inquiry in detail to identify how further to improve our structures, policies, procurement and training. Since 2010, the Ministry of Defence (MOD) has implemented wide-ranging reforms to how it is structured and managed. This has clarified responsibilities, strengthened accountability and empowered the single Services. The Defence Secretary confirmed to the Defence Select Committee on 19 July that he has established a team to go through the report and make sure that the proper lessons are learned. This team will identify all of the areas where MOD needs to take action to improve its performance in the light of Sir John Chilcot's findings.</p>",,"Earl Howe",,"2016-07-26T15:29:12.023Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539193/answer","Biography information for Earl Howe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539193/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539193/answer",,,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2016-07-18","Iraq Committee of Inquiry","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the report by Sir John Chilcot on the Iraq War, whether they have any plans to reform the decision-making process within the Ministry of Defence and place the Armed Forces under the command of the Chief of Defence Staff.","false","Biography information for Lord Richards of Herstmonceux",,"Lord Richards of Herstmonceux","HL1269"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539194","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-08-02","<p>In the last Parliament, the Cabinet asked for further detailed work to understand the uncertainties around cost and demand for resettlement of the British Indian Ocean Territory. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office, the Department for International Development and the Ministry of Defence, have refined uncertainties around costs, and a 12 week public consultation was carried out to clarify demand. The results of the consultation were published in January 2016. Officials are now carrying out remaining work on the options available before the Prime Minister, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Maidenhead (Mrs May), takes a final decision on the policy. There is no date yet when an announcement on possible resettlement will be made. Developments will be announced to Parliament and the public in due course.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-08-02T13:22:50.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539194/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539194/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539194/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","Ilois: Resettlement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, in the light of the comments by Lord Mance in the Supreme Court’s judgment in <i>R (on the application of Bancoult (No 2)) v Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs </i>[2016] UKSC 35 that a refusal to allow resettlement of the Chagos Islands could be judicially reviewed as potentially "irrational, unreasonable and/or disproportionate", what steps they plan to take to reach a reasoned decision on the issue of resettlement as quickly as possible.","false","Biography information for Lord Steel of Aikwood",,"Lord Steel of Aikwood","HL1270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539195","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-08-02","We are not aware of any plans by Mauritius for a resolution at the next UN General Assembly regarding the resettlement of Chagos islanders to be referred to the International Court of Justice (ICC). On 17 May the Prime Minister of Mauritius expressed to the Mauritian Parliament his intention to seek a referral by the UN General Assembly to the ICC this autumn, in order to obtain an advisory opinion in relation to sovereignty of the British Indian Ocean Territory (BIOT). We would not support any such resolution as we are in no doubt about British sovereignty over BIOT.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-08-02T13:24:04.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539195/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539195/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539195/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","Ilois: Resettlement","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will support the resolution from Mauritius at the forthcoming UN General Assembly calling for the matter of the resettlement of Chagos islanders to be referred to the International Court of Justice.","false","Biography information for Lord Steel of Aikwood",,"Lord Steel of Aikwood","HL1271"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539196","Home Office","false","2016-07-26","<p>Border Force has carried out a significant transformation programme at Port of Tyne to improve border security and customer service. Joint investment with the port operator in new infrastructure has significantly reduced passenger processing times and the port operator has confirmed a noticeable improvement compared to previous years.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-26T15:42:40.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539196/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539196/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539196/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Immigration Controls: Newcastle upon Tyne","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether, in order to welcome tourists to Scotland and the North of England, they plan to instruct the Border Agency to reduce its processing time of vehicles at Newcastle arriving off the ferry from Amsterdam.","false","Biography information for Lord Steel of Aikwood",,"Lord Steel of Aikwood","HL1272"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539197","Department for Education","false","2016-07-28","<p>Design and Technology (D&amp;T) is a subject that can inspire and equip young people for further study and careers in a range of design and engineering fields. Our reforms to the D&amp;T curriculum and qualifications move the subject on from its craft-based routes to be aligned with high-tech industry practice.</p><p> </p><p>The English Baccalaureate (EBacc) has been designed to be limited in size to provide a rigorous academic core whilst leaving space in the curriculum for pupils to study other subjects of their choice. On average, pupils in state-funded schools enter nine GCSEs and equivalent qualifications, rising to more than ten for more able pupils. As the EBacc covers up to eight GCSEs, this leaves room for other choices, including D&amp;T.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-07-28T14:34:41.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539197/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539197/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539197/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-18","Design and Technology","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what consideration they have given to including Design and Technology as a science option within the English Baccalaureate.","false","Biography information for Lord Wills",,"Lord Wills","HL1273"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539198","Department for Education","false","2016-07-28","<p>Design and Technology (D&amp;T) is part of the national curriculum, and is therefore a compulsory subject in maintained schools for pupils aged 5 to 14. The national curriculum is a benchmark of an excellent, academically rigorous education that academies can use and improve upon. The Department does not collect information on how many schools do not include D&amp;T as part of their curriculum.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-07-28T14:30:44.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539198/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539198/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539198/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-18","Design and Technology","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government in how many schools Design and Technology is not part of the curriculum.","false","Biography information for Lord Wills",,"Lord Wills","HL1274"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539199","Department for Education","false","2016-07-28","<p>The latest published data, from 30 June 2016, shows that 1,370 applications have been submitted for Design and Technology ITT courses, either to a university or a school-led route.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-07-28T14:30:59.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539199/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539199/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539199/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-18","Design and Technology","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many people have applied to study Design and Technology in teacher training colleges.","false","Biography information for Lord Wills",,"Lord Wills","HL1275"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539200","Department for Education","false","2016-07-28","<p>Science, technology, engineering and mathematics are vital subjects in our modern economy and there is a widespread demand for employees with knowledge and skills in these subjects. That is why we have worked closely with key organisations in the sector, such as the James Dyson Foundation, the Design and Technology Association and the Royal Academy of Engineering to ensure the content of Design and Technology curriculum and qualifications set out the knowledge and skills sought by leading engineering employers and are aligned with high-tech industry practice. The new GCSE and A level begin to be taught from September 2017.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-07-28T14:31:27.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539200/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539200/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539200/answer",,,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-07-18","Design and Technology","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the contribution of Design and Technology studies to the UK economy.","false","Biography information for Lord Wills",,"Lord Wills","HL1276"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539201","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-20","<p>Community Land Trusts (CLTs) are non-profit local organisations set up and run by local people to develop and manage homes and other community assets. They will be regulated according to the specific legal form they have decided is appropriate for their objectives. Consequently, the Department does not retain any central records on CLTs or their trustees.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-07-20T16:08:05.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539201/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539201/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539201/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-18","Community Land Trusts","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are aware of any situations where trustees of community land trusts who are also members of parish councils have been prevented from carrying out their duties due to their interests being inaccurately declared as personal and prejudicial, and if so, what advice they plan to provide to all involved to resolve such situations.","false","Biography information for Baroness Bakewell of Hardington Mandeville",,"Baroness Bakewell of Hardington Mandeville","HL1277"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539202","Home Office","false","2016-07-29","<p>There are no immediate plans for changes to the format or colour of the UK passport. Parliament will be informed of any changes to the passport following UK withdrawal from the European Union</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-29T12:16:21.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539202/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539202/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539202/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Passports","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have plans to (1) change the colour of the current British passport from maroon to dark blue, and (2) remove the words "European Union" from British passports.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL1278"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539203","Department of Health","false","2016-07-26","<p>The Department does not itself conduct research, but funds research through the National Institute for Health Research (NIHR) and the Department’s Policy Research Programme (PRP). The NIHR and the PRP have not funded specific research into the possible mental and psychological impact on children of using Twitter and Facebook and have no plans to commission research on this topic. In 2014-15 (the latest year for which data is currently available), the NIHR invested £72.6 million in research in mental health, including the mental health of children.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-07-26T13:21:05.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539203/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539203/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539203/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Children: Social Media","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have conducted any research into the possible mental and psychological impact on children of using Twitter and Facebook; and if not, whether they plan to do so.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL1279"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539204","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-21","<p>Civil servants manage departmental social media accounts, but not individual MP Twitter handles.</p>",,"Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen",,"2016-07-21T15:51:37.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539204/answer","Biography information for Baroness Chisholm of Owlpen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539204/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539204/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-18","Ministers: Twitter","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government which ministers have official ministerial Twitter accounts; and whether they have plans to close those accounts.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL1280"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539205","Department of Health","false","2016-07-26","<p>In June 2014 the General Medical Council (GMC) was given powers to carry out proportionate language controls on all applicants from the European Economic Area (EEA) to ensure that doctors have the necessary English language skills to practise safely in the United Kingdom. In addition the GMC was given powers to take fitness to practise action if a doctor working in the UK has insufficient language skills to carry out their job safely. Doctors must register with the GMC to practise in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>Since June 2014 a total of 1,659 doctors from the EEA have been unable to demonstrate to the GMC that they have sufficient language skills to practise safely in the UK; 564 of those doctors have gone on to reach the standard required by the GMC and have been issued with a licence to practise.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL1282","2016-07-26T13:25:31.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539205/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539205/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539205/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Doctors: Migrant Workers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to implement English language checks on doctors who have come from other EU countries to test their knowledge of clinical English rather than general social English.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL1281"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539206","Department of Health","false","2016-07-26","<p>In June 2014 the General Medical Council (GMC) was given powers to carry out proportionate language controls on all applicants from the European Economic Area (EEA) to ensure that doctors have the necessary English language skills to practise safely in the United Kingdom. In addition the GMC was given powers to take fitness to practise action if a doctor working in the UK has insufficient language skills to carry out their job safely. Doctors must register with the GMC to practise in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>Since June 2014 a total of 1,659 doctors from the EEA have been unable to demonstrate to the GMC that they have sufficient language skills to practise safely in the UK; 564 of those doctors have gone on to reach the standard required by the GMC and have been issued with a licence to practise.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL1281","2016-07-26T13:25:31.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539206/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539206/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539206/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Doctors: Migrant Workers","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what estimate they have made of the number of doctors from other EU countries who have inadequate clinical English language skills.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL1282"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539207","Department of Health","false","2016-07-25","<p>The Government has no plans to issue instructions to ignore the Working Time Directive (WTD).</p><p> </p><p>There will be no immediate changes to our relationship with the European Union. We remain a part of the EU until negotiations are concluded, which could take up two years or more if agreement isn’t reached. While the United Kingdom remains a member of the EU, we must meet our obligations as a member of the EU, including the WTD.</p><p><br> It is the responsibility of individual National Health Service trusts to ensure service rotas are compliant with the WTD.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-07-25T10:42:56.513Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539207/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539207/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539207/answer",,,,,,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-07-18","Doctors: Working Hours","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to issue instructions to NHS Trusts to draw up doctors' schedules that ignore the EU Working Time Directive.","false","Biography information for Lord Blencathra",,"Lord Blencathra","HL1283"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539208","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-08-01","<p>The Government of Sudan played a constructive role in the Intergovernmental Authority on Development peace process in South Sudan and the recent meeting of regional Foreign Ministers on 11 July in Nairobi. We are working closely with all regional countries to end the violence in South Sudan.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-08-01T15:59:02.503Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539208/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539208/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539208/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","South Sudan: Armed Conflict","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the government of Sudan's attitude and approach towards the conflict in South Sudan, and whether it will contribute to peace and stability in South Sudan.","false","Biography information for Lord Sheikh",,"Lord Sheikh","HL1284"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539209","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-26","<p>Since 2014, DFID Sudan has provided £10.4 million to address the humanitarian needs of South Sudanese refugees arriving in Sudan. The assistance has been in the areas of emergency food distribution, water and sanitation, education, and protection activities in the areas of White Nile State and Kordofan states. We are currently discussing with humanitarian partners in Sudan further contributions of approximately £3 million to be disbursed in the coming months.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to monitor the situation and provide further support if required.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-07-26T15:35:50.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539209/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539209/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539209/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-18","South Sudan: Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what humanitarian support and assistance they have (1) provided, and (2) plan to provide, for South Sudanese refugees in Sudan.","false","Biography information for Lord Sheikh",,"Lord Sheikh","HL1285"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539210","Department for International Development","false","2016-07-28","<p>On the basis of an agreement between the World Food Programme (WFP) and the governments of Sudan and South Sudan, the WFP have been working with relevant government authorities in both countries and the region to ensure that their planes are able to deliver much needed humanitarian supplies into South Sudan. For instance, from January to June 2016 alone WFP managed to deliver close to 21,300 metric tons of cereals, pulses and vegetable oil to Upper Nile state. With the six-month extension to this agreement, WFP plans to deliver another 10,000 metric tons of food from Sudan to South Sudan. This represents a pragmatic approach to delivering vital humanitarian assistance to those affected by the conflict in South Sudan, and we welcome the support of the Government of Sudan in facilitating the delivery of food assistance across the border.</p><p> </p><p>DFID Sudan and DFID South Sudan are monitoring the situation in relation to the ongoing crisis in South Sudan, and will keep working closely with WFP to help maintain essential transport corridors for humanitarian assistance.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-07-28T14:14:19.667Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539210/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539210/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539210/answer",,,,,,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-07-18","South Sudan: Humanitarian Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the effectiveness of the agreement between the governments of Sudan and South Sudan and the World Food Programme to transport humanitarian assistance to South Sudan via Sudan, in the light of that agreement's extension.","false","Biography information for Lord Sheikh",,"Lord Sheikh","HL1286"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539211","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-08-01","<p>The UK continues to work closely with its Troika partners the US and Norway. The visit by the US’s Special Envoy to Sudan underlines the benefits of the ongoing strategic dialogue between the UK and the Government of Sudan, which allows us to raise issues of concern directly with the Government of Sudan.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-08-01T16:00:00.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539211/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539211/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539211/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","Sudan: Foreign Relations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the visit by the US’s Special Envoy for Sudan, Donald Booth, to Sudan in June, and of any lessons that could be learnt from that visit for UK–Sudan relations.","false","Biography information for Lord Sheikh",,"Lord Sheikh","HL1287"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539212","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-08-01","<p>Sudan has an important role in tackling the threat of the various extremist groups that operate in region. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office’s Africa Director discussed countering extremism with the Government of Sudan during his visit to Khartoum in March, and we are encouraging them to play a constructive role.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-08-01T16:00:28.4Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539212/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539212/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539212/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","Sudan: Radicalism","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the efforts by the government of Sudan to prevent the influence in Sudan of groups such as Daesh, Boko Haram, and Al Shabaab.","false","Biography information for Lord Sheikh",,"Lord Sheikh","HL1288"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539213","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-08-01","<p>The British Council already has a number of projects in Sudan which aim to strengthen cultural and educational relations. They have over 200 partner schools, engage with over 250,000 people in a national English teacher training programme and have provided English language training to 500 leading journalists. Sudan has also been added as a priority country for the British Council’s new £30m Cultural Protection Fund, and the British Council office in Khartoum is in discussion with a range of partners to develop proposals. Our Embassy in Khartoum also oversees the Chevening scholarship programme for highly talented Sudanese with leadership potential to pursue masters degrees in the UK.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-08-01T16:00:56.773Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539213/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539213/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539213/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","Sudan: Foreign Relations","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have any plans to promote stronger educational and cultural links between the UK and Sudan.","false","Biography information for Lord Sheikh",,"Lord Sheikh","HL1289"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539214","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-07-25","<p>As previously stated in the House of Commons, Government is reviewing the situation and we hope to announce details of a review in due course.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ashton of Hyde",,"2016-07-25T13:12:53.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539214/answer","Biography information for Lord Ashton of Hyde","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539214/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539214/answer",,,,,,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-07-18","Gaming Machines","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what progress has been made in setting a date for the Triennial Review of gaming machine stakes and prizes.","false","Biography information for Lord Smith of Hindhead",,"Lord Smith of Hindhead","HL1290"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539215","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-08-01","<p>The decision to equalise the State Pension age for men and women dates back to 1995 and addresses a longstanding inequality. Since April 2010, women’s State Pension age has been gradually increasing for those born after 6 April 1950. Following sharp increases in life expectancy projections, and therefore the increase in the number of people living longer in retirement, this timetable was accelerated by the Pensions Act 2011.</p><p>The Government listened to concerns expressed by those affected by the Pension Act 2011 changes, and took action to limit the maximum change to State Pension age to 18 months, a concession worth over £1billion.</p><p>All those affected by the faster equalisation timetable will reach State Pension age following the introduction of the new State Pension, which is more generous for many women who have historically done poorly under the current system.</p><p>The average woman reaching State Pension age in the first forty years of the new State Pension is estimated to receive 10 per cent more State Pension over her lifetime than the average man.</p><p>Women retiring today can still expect to receive the State Pension for 26 years on average – several years longer than men. And this generation of women will spend a higher proportion of their lives in retirement than any before.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-08-01T14:09:13.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539215/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539215/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539215/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-18","State Retirement Pensions: Females","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the continuing impact of the alterations to the state pension age on women born in the 1950s, on or after 6 April 1951.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL1291"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539216","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-08-01","<p>Transitional arrangements are already in place. At the time of the Pensions Act 2011 the government introduced a concession worth £1.1 billion to limit the impact of the rising state pension age on those most affected. The concession capped the maximum delay that anyone would face in claiming their State Pension to 18 months rather than two years, relative to the previous timetable.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-08-01T14:12:19.823Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539216/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539216/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539216/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-18","State Retirement Pensions: Females","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the calls by Women Against State Pension Inequality for transitional state pension arrangements for women born in the 1950s, on or after 6 April 1951.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL1292"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539217","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-08-15","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy will continue to lead on consumer affairs. Margot James MP is the Minister for Small Business, Consumers, and Corporate Responsibility.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-08-15T12:24:29.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539217/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539217/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539217/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-18","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Departmental Responsibilities","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the new Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy will continue to lead on consumer affairs; and if so, which minister has responsibility for that area.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL1293"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539218","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-28","<p>We have introduced fixed term tenancies for all new council tenancies to ensure we get the best use out of our social housing stock and focus this valuable resource on those who need it the most for as long as they need it. This is essential with 1.24 million households on council waiting lists. The changes will apply to new tenants, but will not apply to existing lifetime tenants who remain in their own home.</p><p>We are preparing the regulations which will set out the circumstances in which local authorities may exercise discretion to offer tenants seeking transfer further lifetime tenancies in limited circumstances. These will include where tenants downsize into a smaller home, move for work or to escape harm, including domestic violence. We will ensure that relevant organisations including those working with victims of domestic abuse will be able to feed in their views into the draft regulations.</p><p>We aim to lay the regulations in the Winter.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-07-28T14:30:14.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539218/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539218/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539218/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-18","Security of Tenure: Domestic Abuse","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they propose to lay regulations concerning the right to security of tenure for victims of domestic violence under the Housing and Planning Act 2016, and whether they will first consult organisations working with victims of domestic violence.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL1294"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539219","Home Office","false","2016-07-29","<p>We are working closely with the Department for Work and Pensions to ensure that new recognised refugees apply promptly for any welfare benefit for which they may be eligible and receive the first payment of any benefit for which they qualify before their Home Office support ends.</p><p>We plan to publish our evaluation of this work later this year and will bring forward a change to the current 28-day move-on period if the evaluation shows that to be necessary.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-29T12:16:04.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539219/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539219/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539219/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Refugees","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect to publish the evaluation of the moving on period for those granted refugee status, announced during the passage of the Immigration Act 2016.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL1295"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539220","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-07-21","<p>The change in publication format for the 2014/15 Households Below Average Income (HBAI) National Statistics release was made to bring this report into line with the new standard DWP Statistics template, with the aim of giving more focussed and accessible publications, without sacrificing the breadth of statistical analysis previously published.</p><p> </p><p>No information has been lost from this publication, rather this restructuring is intended to allow the lay user to better understand these important statistics.</p><p> </p><p>This approach is in line with the UK Statistics Authority’s “Better Statistics, Better Decisions” strategy and the specific change in format for HBAI was trailed in a Statistical Notice released in April 2016.</p>",,"Lord Freud",,"2016-07-21T14:07:37.403Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539220/answer","Biography information for Lord Freud","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539220/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539220/answer",,,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-07-18","Low Incomes: Statistics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why the Department for Work and Pensions report of the Household Below Average Income Statistics was over 100 pages in length in previous years and this year is 13 pages in length; and why this year's report contains details published in Excel tables only.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL1296"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539221","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-07-29","<p>Following its May 2016 Article IV Consultation with Zimbabwe, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) noted that “despite the adverse environment, the authorities have reduced the fiscal deficit in both 2014 and 2015. They have started to rationalise public expenditures by implementing recommendations from the 2015 civil service audit. They are also amending the Public Financial Management and Procurement Acts. The Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe has taken measures to restore confidence in the financial sector. All banks in operations now have capital buffers above the minimum requirements”. The IMF assessment did not cover political reform.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-07-29T13:59:20.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539221/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539221/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539221/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","Zimbabwe: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 14 July (HL1012) in which they stated that the IMF "noted Zimbabwe's good progress and encouraged further reforms", what policies or actions they classify as examples of Zimbabwe's good progress on either economic or political reform.","false","Biography information for Lord Oates",,"Lord Oates","HL1297"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539222","Department for Transport","false","2016-07-27","<p>Trains where the driver has responsibility for all aspects of operation, including the doors (known in the industry as ‘Driver Only Operation’) have been in service in Great Britain for over 30 years.</p><p> </p><p>The Office of Rail and Road (ORR), in its role as the independent railway safety regulator, has scrutinised this approach and is satisfied that, with suitable equipment, proper procedures and competent staff in place, it is a safe method of working.</p><p> </p><p>A number of projects have been published by RSSB on various aspects of Driver Only Operation on passenger trains. Its research has concluded that, when properly managed, there are no increased risks from dispatching a train without a guard being present.</p><p> </p><p>Department for Transport officials regularly meet with ORR and RSSB representatives to discuss a variety of railway safety issues including Driver Only Operation.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2016-07-27T14:50:44.617Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539222/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539222/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539222/answer",,,,,,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-07-18","Railways: Safety","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the policy of the Rail Safety and Standards Board (RSSB) and of the Office of Road and Rail (ORR) on the circumstances in which Driver-Only Operation can safely be implemented; and whether they have had discussions with RSSB and ORR on that issue.","false","Biography information for Baroness Randerson",,"Baroness Randerson","HL1298"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539223","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-08-01","<p>The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson), issued a statement on 17 July expressing concerns about the Bahraini High Administrative Court’s decision to dissolve the main Bahraini Shia opposition political society Al Wefaq. We continue to follow the case closely. We have urged the Government of Bahrain to protect political freedoms and representation for all Bahraini citizens and to encourage all sides to engage in constructive and inclusive dialogue to promote social cohesion and inclusivity.</p><p>We regularly discuss human rights and reform with the Government of Bahrain and it is a standing agenda item for the biannual UK-Bahrain Joint Working Group meeting, held most recently in June 2016. The former Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Runnymede and Weybridge (Mr Hammond), also raised concerns about recent developments with the Bahraini Foreign Minister on 14 June, and during his visit to Bahrain on 30 May.</p><p>We have begun work on the future UK maritime hub at Mina Salman in Bahrain, HMS Juffair, to support Royal Navy deployments. We continue to maintain a naval presence which includes mine countermeasure ships, frigates, destroyers and maritime helicopters to contribute to the stability of the region and to make sure vital sea lanes remain open in the region.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-08-01T16:02:18.223Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539223/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539223/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539223/answer",,,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-07-18","Bahrain: Politics and Government","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their response to the recent actions of the government of Bahrain towards the main Shia opposition group; what is their assessment of the state of human rights in that country; and whether the development of a new Royal Naval base in Bahrain is progressing.","false","Biography information for Lord Kilclooney",,"Lord Kilclooney","HL1299"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539224","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-07-26","<p>Under the Consumer Rights Act 2015 software must be of satisfactory quality, which includes durability for a period a consumer can reasonably expect. If it is not, the consumer may be entitled to a remedy under the Act, for example, a repair or replacement of the software or, if this is not possible, the right to demand some money back. The Government has no plans to require the release of the source code of unsupported software to a third party.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-07-26T13:26:09.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539224/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539224/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539224/answer",,,,,,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-07-18","Computer Software","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they will take action to support users of software that is no longer supported by the original vendor, for example by requiring the release of the source code of unsupported software to a third party.","false","Biography information for Lord Howarth of Newport",,"Lord Howarth of Newport","HL1300"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539225","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-08-01","<p>It is too early to say. Whatever the impact, this government remains committed to increasing the supply of homes for the 86 percent of people who aspire to own their own home. The Spending Review doubled the housing budget and set out the most ambitious affordable housing programme since the 1970s, which will help us to achieve our ambition of delivering one million homes.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-08-01T11:45:31.71Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539225/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539225/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539225/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-18","Housing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether Brexit will increase, decrease, or have no material impact on, the need for more housing in England.","false","Biography information for Lord Inglewood",,"Lord Inglewood","HL1301"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539226","Home Office","false","2016-07-29","<p>The EU Implementing Regulation 2015/2403 on deactivation standards which came into force on 8 April 2016 sets new technical specifications for deactivated weapons.</p><p>Clause 114 of the Policing and Crime Bill creates a specific new offence to sell or gift a weapon that has not been deactivated to the new EU Deactivation Standard.</p><p>We have received representations from a small number of interested parties who have been concerned that the EU specification is not as effective as the previous UK standards. In addition, we were contacted by members of re-enactment and living history societies wishing to travel to France with their firearms to participate in commemorative events linked to the D-Day landings and the Battle of the Somme.</p><p>We have published guidance on the Regulation which includes requirements for additional measures for deactivated weapons brought into the UK. These measures, which go beyond the EU specification in a small number of areas, were introduced to align the requirements more closely with the previous UK standards. We have also worked with the UK Proof Houses to ensure that certification to the new standards is prioritised for re-enactors wishing to travel with their firearms.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-29T12:13:25.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539226/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539226/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539226/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Firearms","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what representations they have received from interested parties about the recent EU deactivation specification as it applies to deactivated historical firearms as defined in the Policing and Crime Bill.","false","Biography information for Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts",,"Lord Hodgson of Astley Abbotts","HL1302"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539227","Home Office","false","2016-07-29","<p>The Government is in the process of identifying a provider of independent child trafficking advocates and three early adopter sites.</p><p>To ensure we assess the revised independent child trafficking advocates model appropriately, early adopter sites will cover areas with different demographics as well as having a range of experiences of working with trafficked children.</p><p>Officials are developing an outcomes framework with support from a wide selection of academics and professionals who have expertise and experience in working with local authorities and trafficked children.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-07-29T12:14:58.443Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539227/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539227/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539227/answer",,,,,,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-07-18","Human Trafficking: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the remarks by the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for the Home Department, Karen Bradley MP (HC Deb, cols 33WH–54WH), on independent advocates for trafficked children, (1) what is the timetable for establishing early adopter sites of independent child trafficking advocates, (2) what geographic areas will constitute a site for these trials, and (3) what mechanisms will be put in place for monitoring the outcomes of children who received an advocate in the first phase of these trials.","false","Biography information for Lord McColl of Dulwich",,"Lord McColl of Dulwich","HL1303"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539479","Attorney General","false","2016-07-25","<p>Whilst the Attorney General’s Office can ask the Court of Appeal to review a sentence which is considered to be unduly lenient, the Law Officers have no power to intervene when a sentence is too harsh. Therefore there have been no referrals to the Court of Appeal on the grounds that a sentence was unduly harsh.</p><p> </p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-07-25T10:43:25.807Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539479/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539479/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539479/answer",,,,,,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-07-18","Sentencing: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, on how many occasions the Law Officers referred a criminal sentence to the Court for Appeal for review on the grounds that it was unduly harsh in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","43056"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539480","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-26","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2016-07-26T14:34:27.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539480/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539480/answer","UKSA Response to 43043.pdf","UKSA Letter to Member - Air Pollution","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539480/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-18","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many deaths have been caused by air pollution in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","43043"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539481","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-21","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","43014","2016-07-21T08:04:35.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539481/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539481/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539481/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-18","Economic and Domestic Affairs Secretariat: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much the Economic and Domestic Affairs secretariat spent on legal advice relating to Freedom of Information cases in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","43013"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539482","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-21","<p>The information requested is not held centrally and could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer","43013","2016-07-21T08:04:35.697Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539482/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539482/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539482/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-18","Cabinet Office: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much the Propriety and Ethics Unit spent on legal advice relating to Freedom of Information cases in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","43014"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539483","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-21","<p>There are currently 11 members of the Senior Civil Service who are in receipt of a private secretary allowance. Staff at Band B2 or above who currently work in the Private Office of a Director General, Permanent Secretary or Minister are entitled to receive the Private Office allowance. The authorisation process is robustly enforced within the department, with accountability resting with the Head of Private Office Group.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-07-21T08:42:57.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539483/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539483/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539483/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-18","Cabinet Office: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 18 July 2016 to Question 42517, how many members of staff who are in receipt of a private secretary allowance are Senior Civil Servants.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","43022"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539484","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-21","<p>As yet, no consideration has been given, or decisions taken, about the laws or policies relevant to EU nationals applying for, or being employed in civil service posts.</p>","Haltemprice and Howden","Mr David Davis",,"2016-07-21T09:15:35.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539484/answer","Biography information for Mr David Davis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539484/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539484/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-18","Civil Servants: EU Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the Government plans to introduce further restrictions on the posts that EU nationals are able to (a) work in and (b) apply for within the Civil Service; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","42964"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539485","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-21","<p>There have been a number of Ministerial and government appointments announced recently. Administrative support for those appointments has yet to be concluded.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-07-21T08:46:27.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539485/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539485/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539485/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-18","Extended Ministerial Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many extended Ministerial offices have been shut down since 13 July 2016.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","42978"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539486","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-22","<p>Severance payments are in the process of being calculated. Details of the costs will be published in due course.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-07-22T10:02:34.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539486/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539486/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539486/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-18","Cabinet Office: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what severance pay has been granted to the special advisers that left his Department in the last week.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","43066"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539487","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-20","<p>The Prime Minister will consider all such appointments, including that of the anti-corruption champion, in due course.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-07-20T08:57:44.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539487/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539487/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539487/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-18","Eric Pickles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether the hon. Member for Brentwood and Ongar has retained his role as the Government's Anti-Corruption Champion.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Ashworth","Leicester South","Jonathan Ashworth","43068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539488","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-22","<p>Having re-reviewed the numbers and status of the FTA I can confirm that 28 people in IPA are employed through Fixed Term Appointments (we have now removed people who have since moved on either due to their appointment coming to an end or moving to other roles either within Cabinet Office or across wider government).</p><p>These members of staff cost £1,937,818 annually out of an overall IPA budget of £14,463,994.</p><p>To put this in context IPA oversees projects with whole life costs of well over £500bn.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-07-22T10:05:10.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539488/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539488/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539488/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-18","Infrastructure and Projects Authority","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 18 July 2016 to Question 42548, what the cost to the public purse is of employing the 37 people referred to in that Answer.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","43173"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539489","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-22","<p>If the Accelerate programme runs in future years, then the Cabinet Office will promote take-up of the programme through the intranet and will support disabled applicants through the Cabinet Office Disability Network.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-07-22T10:01:20.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539489/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539489/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539489/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-18","Cabinet Office: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 18 July 2016 to Question 42551, if he will take steps to improve take-up of the Accelerate programme by disabled members of staff.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","43174"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539490","Cabinet Office","false","2016-07-21","<p>No pay rises have been awarded to Special Advisers in the Cabinet Office since 17 December 2015.</p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-07-21T08:41:28.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539490/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539490/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539490/answer",,,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-07-18","Cabinet Office: Ministerial Policy Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, whether any pay rises were awarded to special advisers in the Cabinet Office since 17 December 2015.","false","Biography information for Tom Watson","West Bromwich East","Tom Watson","43227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539491","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-21","<p>The people of the UK have voted to leave the EU. It would not be appropriate to commit, without due consideration, to continuing to spend money over a long period as if we had not voted to leave the EU. But the Government remains committed to encouraging economic growth across the regions and nations of the UK. The Government is therefore carefully considering the use of these funds and will make an announcement on EU funding in due course.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-07-21T13:58:55.24Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539491/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539491/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539491/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-18","Public Expenditure: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to make additional funding available to Wales after the UK's exit from the European Union.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","43229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539492","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-21","<p>Health functions have been devolved to Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland. This means responsibility for the infected blood payment schemes is a matter for those devolved administrations. The proposals for reform, set out in the government’s consultation response document published July 13, are for England only.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-07-21T14:05:02.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539492/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539492/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539492/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-18","Blood: Contamination","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to make additional funding available to the Welsh Health Service as a result of the decision to offer increased annual payments to victims of contaminated blood.","false","Biography information for Nia Griffith","Llanelli","Nia Griffith","43230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539493","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-26","<p>The questions on Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) and Financial Services Authority fees and levies are both a matter for the FCA, who are operationally independent from Government.</p><p> </p><p>The questions have been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the Honorable Member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-07-26T10:05:04.8Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539493/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539493/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539493/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-18","Financial Services: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what revenue was received by the (a) Financial Conduct Authority and (b) Financial Services Authority from fees and levies payable by regulated firms in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for James Cartlidge","South Suffolk","James Cartlidge","43168"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539494","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-21","<p>In line with the all-party Smith Commission, the UK and Scottish Governments have agreed that receipts from the first 10p of the standard rate of VAT and the first 2.5p of the reduced rate of VAT in Scotland will be assigned to the Scottish Government from 2019-20. The UK Government is getting on with implementing that agreement.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-07-21T11:02:48.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539494/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539494/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539494/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-18","VAT: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to devolve the setting of VAT rates to the Scottish Parliament after the withdrawal of the UK from the EU.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre  Brock","43166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539495","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-26","<p>The tax treaty with Malawi has been renegotiated, though signature has been delayed by a number of factors. Although the UK’s starting point in negotiations is based closely on the OECD model double taxation convention, the Government recognises that developing countries may have a preference for some of the provisions of the UN model. Treaties the UK has recently signed demonstrate that we are willing to accommodate some of those preferences as part of a balanced agreement.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-07-26T07:56:32.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539495/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539495/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539495/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-18","Double Taxation: Malawi","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will use the UN Model Double Taxation Convention 2011 as the template when renewing the UK tax treaty with Malawi.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","43133"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539496","HM Treasury","false","2016-07-26","<p>As announced at Budget 2016, the government will consult on the duty treatment of heated tobacco products later this year.</p><p> </p><p>Heated tobacco products are a recent innovation in the tobacco market and are not directly captured by current legislation, though the tobacco they contain is subject to excise duty under current legislation.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-07-26T07:57:33.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539496/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539496/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539496/answer",,,,,,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-07-18","Tobacco: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if his Department will take steps to ensure that all heated tobacco-based products are subject to the same excise rates.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","42954"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539499","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-21","<p>One person without a home is one too many and we are committed to doing all we can to prevent homelessness. That is why we have increased central investment to tackle homelessness over the next four years to £139 million. This includes a new £10 million fund to support innovative ways to prevent and reduce rough sleeping, and a new £10 million Social Impact Bond to support rough sleepers with the most complex needs. We also announced at Budget £100 million of funding for low-cost move-on accommodation, including for rough sleepers leaving hostels.</p><p>DCLG publishes annual statistics on the number of people seen sleeping rough on a single night by local authority. These are available at: https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/homelessness-statistics</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-07-21T16:12:20.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539499/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539499/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539499/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-18","Sleeping Rough: Redcar and Cleveland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what estimate he has made of the number of people rough sleeping in Redcar and Cleveland in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Anna Turley","Redcar","Anna Turley","42966"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539500","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-07-21","<p>The Housing &amp; Planning Act 2016 extended the grounds for seeking a Rent Repayment Order to include illegal eviction, breach of a banning order or failure to comply with a statutory notice. It is envisaged that each of these will also be banning order offences. Where a person or organisation has been convicted of a banning order offence, local authorities will be encouraged to record that information in the database of rogue landlords and property agents. This will enable government to monitor how frequently Rent Repayment Orders are used.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-07-21T15:57:32.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539500/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539500/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539500/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-18","Rent Repayment Orders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what plans he has to monitor the use of extended Rent Repayment Orders.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","42976"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539501","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-08-01","<p>The Government is committed to addressing the supply of new land for housing. The Public Land for Housing programme has set an ambition to dispose of surplus government-owned land in England with capacity for at least 160,000 homes by 2020. And at Budget 2016 the Chancellor announced a local government land ambition to release land with the capacity for a further 160,000 homes. <br> <br> Individual local planning authorities will decide the type and number of homes developed on the land released - including those for disabled people - in order to meet local need. <br> <br> We have put in place new, flexible Building Regulations which allow local authorities to apply appropriate access standards for new homes to meet the needs of their communities while ensuring that development can happen. Building regulations require minimum standards of accessibility for all new dwellings. Local authorities are able to set policies for a proportion of new development to be built to higher standards of accessibility in order to meet local needs in accordance with national planning policy and guidance. <br> <br> The Government is committed to helping older and disabled people to live independently and safely in their own homes for as a long as possible. The Disabled Facilities Grant funds the provision of home adaptations (including stair lifts, level access showers and in some instances home extensions) to help older and disabled people to live as comfortably, safely and independently as possible in their own homes for longer. Since 2010 we have invested over a billion pounds into the grant providing around 250,000 adaptations to older and disabled people's homes in England. <br> <br> Government is also boosting the supply of specialised housing through the Care and Support Specialised Housing Fund, with 79 schemes receiving more than £84.2 million to develop up to 2,000 affordable homes over the next few years.</p>","Croydon Central","Gavin Barwell",,"2016-08-01T10:42:55.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539501/answer","Biography information for Lord Barwell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539501/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/539501/answer",,,,,,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-07-18","Housing: Construction","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether the Government is ensuring that programmes involving the regeneration of public land require a proportion of the new homes delivered to be accessible for disabled people.","false","Biography information for Mr David Anderson","Blaydon","Mr David Anderson","42999"
